<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Villagers Killed by Indian Border Guards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Indian border guards Tuesday once
again intruded into Bangladesh and shot dead two brothers at
frontier village Khalisa Kotal in Kurigram district, some 400
kilometers northwest of Dhaka, the United News of Bangladesh (UNB)
reported.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said tensions mounted in the area as India's Border
Security Force (BSF) equipped with heavy guns hoisted red flags in
their territory while Bangladesh Rifles (BDR) personnel were
reinforced to face any situation.
</P>
<P>
Locals said the BSF men crossed into Khalisa Kotal village near
No. 934 border demarcation pillar and gunned down Sagiruddin, 30,
and Ekramul, 26, who were working in the field at about 8:30 am.
</P>
<P>
"The BSF men intruded in the Bangladesh territory, ordered the
working brothers to quit. As they refused to follow the BSF
command, they were shot," said a spot report.
</P>
<P>
Confirming the deaths, a BDR source said, "The matter will be
strongly protested. We have also reinforced our troops to face any
situation."
</P>
<P>
Talking to the UNB, a villager said BSF's "aggression"
heightened recently. Last month, a Bangladeshi national was killed
by the BSF at Karla enclave, three kilometers off Khalisa Kotal
village. 
</P>
</TEXT>
