<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Opens Middle East Summit at Camp David </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
opened a summit with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat on Tuesday at David Camp,
Maryland, hoping that his mediation could help solve the decades-
long conflict between Israel and the Palestinians and reach a
final status agreement between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart told reporters at the
presidential retreat that Clinton already met Arafat outside of
his cabin shortly after noon and was to hold a similar private
session with Barak before bringing the two Middle East leaders
together for their first face-to-face talks at the summit.
</P>
<P>
Before his departure for the Camp David, Clinton said that
Arafat and Barak now face "profound and wrenching" questions that
cannot be resolved without compromise.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said, "Both leaders feel the weight of history but both,
I believe, recognize this is a moment in history which they can
seize. We have an opportunity to bring about a just and enduring
end to the Israeli-Palestinian conflict. This is the key to
lasting peace in the entire Middle East."
</P>
<P>
He said that both Barak and Arafat have demonstrated their
determination to reach an agreement. "In the process, they have
passed the point of no return. The only way forward now is forward.
Both sides must find a way to resolve competing claims, to give
their children the gift of peace."
</P>
<P>
"It will take patience, creativity and courage," he said. "I'll
do everything I can over the coming days to see that this moment
of promise is fulfilled."
</P>
<P>
Clinton admitted that his task to help solve the conflict
between Israel and the Palestinians was very difficult.
</P>
<P>
The remaining tough issues include the status of Jerusalem, the
final border between Israel and the future Palestinian state and
the return of refugees, who fled the first conflict between the
Israelis and the Arabs in 1948.
</P>
<P>
Barak who survived a no-confidence vote in the Israeli
parliament on Monday, has signaled his willingness to expand
considerably the 40 percent of the West Bank he has promised to
the Palestinians, and to extend Palestinians control in Jerusalem
to Arab-populated suburbs.
</P>
<P>
But the Palestinians demand the entire West Bank, captured by
Israel during the 1967 Middle East war, be returned to them and
Jerusalem be the capital of their future Palestinian state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
