<HEADLINE> Private Firms Urged to Fight AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The Global Business Council (
GBC) on HIV and AIDS Tuesday made an impassioned appeal for
companies around the world to take action against AIDS.
</P>
<P>
"This disease is the defining humanitarian crisis of our time,
and yet the corporate response to date has been inadequate given
the scale of the epidemic," said Bill Roedy, new chairman of GBC
and president of MTV Networks International at the 13th
International Aids Conference in Durban, South Africa.
</P>
<P>
"The business community has a key role to play in the fight
against HIV/AIDS... We have no choice but to get involved," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Roedy, also a UNAIDS ambassador, launched a five-point plan to
specify the role business can play in the battle to curtail the
international scourge, including raising public awareness of AIDS,
supporting community education campaigns and encouraging
businesses to get involved in the fight against AIDS.
</P>
<P>
To boost the work of GBC, World Bank president James Wolfensohn
would become GBC's new honorary president, succeeding Nelson
Mandela.
</P>
<P>
In a special statement, Wolfensohn echoed Roedy's call to
business, saying that the private sector has "a pivotal role to
play" given the vast human and material resources at its disposal.
</P>
</TEXT>
