<HEADLINE> Lagos Workers' Strike Suspended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The 21-day wage strike by workers of
Nigeria' s economic capital, Lagos, has been suspended to allow
for further negotiations between the workers and the state
government, a top labor leader announced on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Adams Oshiomhole, president of the Nigeria Labor Congress, the
country's umbrella labor union, announced the decision while
addressing the workers after a four-hour meeting with Lagos
Governor Bola Tinubu.
</P>
<P>
After the federal government announced a new monthly minimum
wage of 7,500 naira for its workers and 5,500 naira for their
state counterparts on May 29, Lagos civil servants demanded the
same amount as the federal workers, a demand rejected by the
government, setting the stage for the strike.
</P>
<P>
A concession by the government to pay the demanded wage only to
junior workers and a graduated salary increase to senior civil
servants was also rejected by the workers.
</P>
<P>
The government later withdrew the offer and reverted to the 5,
500 naira which all the 36 state governors agreed to pay their
workers at a meeting in Abuja last week.
</P>
<P>
The Abuja meeting was called after workers in the states,
demanding a minimum wage of between 6,500 naira and 7,500 naira,
either went on strike or threatened to do so.
</P>
<P>
Explaining the suspension of the strike, Oshiomhole told the
workers that there is need for them to change their "tactics" and
to alleviate the problems being faced by the estimated 6 million
Lagos population.
</P>
<P>
The strike had paralyzed all government activities, closed
public schools, crippled health services, and halted public water
supply. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
