<HEADLINE> Liberia Gets New Vice President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Liberian President Charles Taylor
has endorsed Moses Z. Blah, a comrade of him in the former rebel
forces, the new vice president of the country.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here on Tuesday from Liberia' s capital
Monrovia confirmed that Blah, Liberian ambassador to Libya and
Tunisia, is to replace late Vice President Enoch Dogolea who died
late June in a clinic in Abidjan, Cote d'Ivoire.
</P>
<P>
Blah was unanimously named for the post Monday by the executive
committee of the ruling National Patriotic Party.
</P>
<P>
The Liberian constitution requires the nominee to be confirmed
by parliament. Taylor has set Blah's inauguration for next Monday.
He said Blah would be confirmed because his party dominates the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Blah is little known among Liberians except for his role as a "
special forces" commando in Taylor's erstwhile National Patriotic
Front of Liberia that ignited the Liberian civil war.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Taylor threatened to "personally deal with anyone
spreading rumors" that the late vice president was murdered.
</P>
<P>
One version of rumors has it that the vice president was
poisoned, while another says he was severely flogged by Taylor's
bodyguards for his alleged involvement in a plot to depose the
president.
</P>
<P>
Taylor, who had ordered a "comprehensive autopsy" apparently
based on the persistent rumors, said he would make public the
autopsy report and medical records of the deceased from hospitals
in Spain, France and Cote d'Ivoire for scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
"Thereafter, anyone caught spreading rumors about Dogolea's
death will face the law to prove it," Taylor said on Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
