<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi, Venezuela Vow to Rebalance Oil Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIYADH, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia and Venezuela on
Wednesday committed themselves to work with other major oil
producers to bring balance to the world oil market which has seen
prices hovering at about 30 U.S. dollars per barrel.
</P>
<P>
According to a communique issued after a meeting between Saudi
Oil Minister Ali Bin Ibrahim al-N'aimi and his visiting Venezuelan
counterpart Ali Rodriguez Araque, the two countries pledged to
redress the shortages in the oil market to ease the high price.
</P>
<P>
Both countries agree that the world oil market is stable and
there is no need to raise the production of the Organization of
Petroleum Export Countries at present, the communique said.
</P>
<P>
However, "current situation and the near future outlook for
products point to an imbalanced market," it went on to say, adding
that the two countries would ensure "adequate and timely supplies."
</P>
<P>
Venezuela, along with another OPEC heavy-weight producer Iran,
has until now been opposed to a Saudi proposal to raise oil
production to bring down prices to OPEC's target of 25 dollars a
barrel, saying extra supplies agreed by OPEC in June should be
given time to reach the market.
</P>
<P>
OPEC members agreed at their June 21 meeting to raise daily
production by 708,000 barrels as of July 1. But the hike has so far
been unable to push down the soaring prices.
</P>
<P>
Rodriguez, who is also OPEC president, arrived in Saudi Arabia
on Wednesday from Kuwait, where he had met with Kuwaiti Oil
Minister Sheikh Saud Nasser Al-Sabah, who said later that OPEC
might raise oil production by the end of July if prices remain
high. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
