<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Parliament Approves Maritime Border Pact With Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti National Assembly
(parliament) on Wednesday approved the maritime border agreement
with Saudi Arabia signed earlier this month, the official KUNA news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
All 53 parliamentarians and cabinet ministers present at the
ballot voted in favor of the agreement, which had already been
approved by the Kuwaiti cabinet on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia approved the pact earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
The accord was signed in the Kuwaiti capital by Kuwaiti Foreign
Minister Sabah Al-Jaber Al-Sabah and his Saudi counterpart Saud Al-
Faisal on July 2 during a visit to Kuwait by Saudi Crown Prince
Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz.
</P>
<P>
The deal was designed to settle any border dispute between Saudi
Arabia and Kuwait over their land boundaries, demarcated about 80
years ago, and the sea lines including the Persian Gulf-located al-
Dorah oilfield which is disputed between Kuwait and Iran.
</P>
<P>
The pact gives Kuwait full sovereignty over the Gulf islands of
Karuh and Umm Al-Maradem, Kuwait's southernmost island, as well as
the island of Felka.
</P>
<P>
The pact stipulates that the new Kuwaiti-Saudi maritime border
will be 1.25 nautical miles south of Umm Al-Maradem.
</P>
<P>
The pact also involves common sharing of the rich natural
resources in the area.
</P>
<P>
The agreement between Kuwait and Saudi Arabia will conduce to a
similar settlement with Iran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
