<HEADLINE> A Minute of Silence in Greece for Victims of Terrorism  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ATHENS, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Greece Wednesday held a minute of
silence in all public and government services around the country
in memory of the victims of terrorism in the country.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, local television and radio channels
broadcasted a brief public awareness message condemning terrorism
and urged the Greek people to help wipe out such phenomena because
it was a threat for modern Greece.
</P>
<P>
The message said that terrorism constituted an insult for the
Greeks and the battle against terrorism was a priority, not only
for the state but also for the Greek people, its political culture.
</P>
<P>
The message stressed that it was a commitment undertaken by
the Greek government and the society's objective to continue the
effort aimed at uprooting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's one minute of silence came after the killing by
Greece's November 17 terrorist group of Britain's military attache
in Athens last month.
</P>
<P>
Greece is now cooperating closely with the Scotland Yard in a
bid to bring the killers to justice and Athens is also expected to
sign with the U.S. a police cooperation agreement in the next two
months to help fight terrorism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
