<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Says U.S. Needs Further Interest Rate Hikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal Reserve should
approve additional interest rate hikes to avert a surge in
inflation in a still buoyant U.S. economy, the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) said in a statement released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
While commending the Clinton administration for fiscal and
monetary policies that have contributed to the country's longest
expansion on record, IMF staff warned that questions remained
about its sustainability.
</P>
<P>
In particular, according to the statement released by the U.S.
Treasury Department, there is no way of knowing how much longer
technology-driven increases in productivity will continue to
support growth.
</P>
<P>
What is clear, the statement said, is that "continued domestic
demand growth at a pace well in excess of the productivity-driven
increases in potential output is not sustainable."
</P>
<P>
"If not reined in, such rapid demand growth threatens to
undermine the prospects for sustained non-inflationary growth," it
added.
</P>
<P>
Under such circumstances, according to the IMF, "a further
tightening of monetary policy will be required to ensure that
inflation remains under control."
</P>
<P>
Federal Reserve policy-makers in the 12 months to May 2000
raised short-term interest rates six times in the face of surging
growth, tight labor markets and prospects for upward pressure on
wages.
</P>
<P>
At their June meeting policy-makers reacted to evidence of a
slowdown in U.S. economic momentum by leaving rates unchanged. But
they too said the moderation might be of short duration and
stressed that further rate hikes might be necessary.
</P>
<P>
The statement also reflected IMF staff discomfort with
imbalances in global growth, with the United States serving as the
principal engine for economic activity.
</P>
<P>
Such persistent imbalances, notably in the face of sluggish
growth in Europe and Japan, increase "the risk of an abrupt
reversal with potentially adverse consequences worldwide,"
according to the staff.
</P>
<P>
The statement also urged Washington to resist protectionist
pressures and expressed concern at an increase in anti-dumping
actions by Washington.
</P>
<P>
It in addition called on the United States to increase its
overseas development assistance, noting that in 1999 such aid
accounted for only 0.1 percent of US gross national product.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Proposes Common European Residency Card for Foreigners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Addressing a meeting of European Parliament's Commission on
Public Freedom in Brussels, French Interior Minister Jean-Pierre
Chevenement said that a common residency card will be a progress
and ``an essential judicial instrument'' to integrate and protect
foreign residents in EU countries.
</P>
<P>
France, which issues a 10-year residency card to the foreign
residents employed by French companies or with professional
credits, proposes that EU countries issue a common residency card
of a duration from eight to 12 years.
</P>
<P>
France, which took over the EU rotating presidency this month,
expects EU countries to obtain an agreement in two years instead
of during its presidency which ends on December 31, said
Chevenement.
</P>
<P>
He also said that France hopes that all EU countries will also
adopt a law guaranteeing ``the right of soil'' which automatically
offers nationality to the children born in their countries as
France and the United States have been doing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Congress Urged to Fund Debt Relief for Poor Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Treasury Secretary
Lawrence Summers on Wednesday urged Congress to fund debt relief
for poor nations, saying the issue was "a defining moral,
diplomatic and economic choice" for the United States.
</P>
<P>
In this year's bill for foreign appropriations, House
Republican leaders have slashed to just 82 million U.S. dollars
the Clinton administration's request for 472 million dollars to
fund debt relief.
</P>
<P>
The move undermines Washington's ability to meet its
obligations under the Heavily Indebted Poor Countries (HIPC) plan,
a scheme aimed at cutting the debt burden of the world's poorest
nations in half in return for pledges to use the savings on social
programs such as health and education.
</P>
<P>
"It is imperative for our country economically, morally and
diplomatically to provide this debt relief," Summers said at a new
conference.
</P>
<P>
Foot-dragging in Congress has already stalled debt relief in
Latin America and could likewise imperil debt relief to African
nations, he said.
</P>
<P>
Legislation approved last year by Congress also failed to
provide money for the United States to pay its share of HIPC debt
relief costs.
</P>
<P>
Some lawmakers want to tie the aid to reforms at the World Bank
and the International Monetary Fund, the institutions that manage
the HIPC program.
</P>
<P>
Summers said President Bill Clinton would veto the current bill
before Congress, which he said left "grossly inadequate funds" to
help poor nations fight poverty and disease.
</P>
<P>
If Congress refuses to fund the U.S. obligations, other rich
nations that have signed on to the HIPC plan might renege on their
payments, White House chief economic adviser Gene Sperling warned.
</P>
<P>
Summers and Sperling were joined at the news conference by
members of Congress who support debt relief. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
