<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Castro Calls US Cuban Adjustment Act Killer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Cuban President Fidel Castro called
Wednesday to fight the U.S. Cuban Adjustment Act, describing it
as infamous and killer.
</P>
<P>
Castro delivered a brief speech during a session of the
National Assembly, that emitted a proclamation against the Cuban
Adjustment Act, a U.S. disposition that grants automatic residence
to Cuban illegal emigrants.
</P>
<P>
"I want to give a brief information that will be useful to
understand the need of presenting a hard combat against that
infamous law," said Castro.
</P>
<P>
The president described four cases of operations of emigrants
illegal traffic that involved more than one hundred Cubans,
occurred only one week after the return to the island of minor
Elian Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
He said that in all the cases, occurred between July 5 and 7,
the groups of illegal emigrants, in which there were more than 20
children, were transported in boats that went to the island from
the United States.
</P>
<P>
Under the 1994 and 1995 immigration accords, 20,000 Cubans are
allowed to immigrate to the United States legally.
</P>
<P>
In line with those accords, Cubans trying to enter the United
States illegally who are intercepted at sea must be returned to
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
But unlike other illegal immigrants, Cubans who manage to evade
the Coast Guard and reach US shores are allowed to seek legal
residency and work permits under the U.S. Cuban Adjustment Act
passed in 1966.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentine Trade Surplus Reaches 643 Mln Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Argentina accumulated a 643
million U.S. dollar trade surplus in the first five months of this
year, said Wednesday the National Statistics and Census Institute
(INDEC).
</P>
<P>
Exports amounted to 10.563 billion dollars and imports to 9.92
billion dollars in the first five months of this year, rising by 1.
3 and 3 percent respectively, said INDEC.
</P>
<P>
The country's trade balance had a deficit of 314 million
dollars during the first five months of the year.
</P>
<P>
Import of motor vehicles registered a 20 percent drop in the
first five months of the year, and those of capital goods, 10
percent, compared to the same period of 1999, reported INDEC.
</P>
<P>
The country had a trade surplus with the Southern Common Market
(Mercosur), Chile, the Latin American Integration Association (
ALADI), the Middle East, and South Africa in the first five months
of the year.
</P>
<P>
But it had a deficit with North America, the European Union and
Asia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
