<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuelan Non-Traditional Exports Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Venezuelan non-traditional exports
amounted to 1.632 billion dollars during the first semester of
2000, surging by 18.31 percent over the same period of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The country's non-oil exports started the year with a 60.58
percent recovery in January, going to 264 million dollars,
according to data supplied by the Foreign Trade Bank published
Wednesday by the local press.
</P>
<P>
Non-traditional exports continued increasing in February, but
at a lesser amount, at a rate of 26.4 percent, while March and
April's recorded drops of 5.6 percent and 0.03 percent,
respectively, before recovering.
</P>
<P>
The 43.5 percent increase recorded in May is attributed to the
drawback payments (the devolution of custom duties paid for raw
materials used in export products) by stages, a process started by
the government by the end of April, according to the Foreign Trade
Bank.
</P>
<P>
The intermitency in the payment of the drawback to exporters by
the government caused a deceleration in the amount of non-
traditional exports, that amounted to 276 million dollars in June,
with an inter-annual growth of 11.4 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
