<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IDB Supports Labor Market Modernization in Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American Development
Bank (IDB) announced Wednesday a loan of 200 million U.S. dollars
to continue financing the second phase of Mexico's comprehensive
labor market modernization.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of both phases of the program is 850 million
dollars. The IDB supported the first phase of the program with a
loan of 250 million dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The program includes training support for microenterprise and
small-and medium-sized enterprises, retraining and internships. It
is designed to upgrade labor market skills, reduce unemployment
and promote private sector growth.
</P>
<P>
Under the second phase of the program, elements and mechanisms
to decentralize training extension units will be introduced and
tested, and a job skills certification system will be promoted.
</P>
<P>
The IDB loan is for a 20-year term, with a two-year grace
period, at the variable interest rate, now 6.77 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
