<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt to Amend Election Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak on
Wednesday called for extraordinary meetings of the People's
Assembly (Parliament) and the Shura (Consultative) Council to amend
the election law.
</P>
<P>
The current election law, in force since 1956, has been ruled by
the Constitutional Court as "unconstitutional" because it failed to
provide judicial supervision of the entire election process.
</P>
<P>
The two chambers of Parliament will meet on Saturday and Sunday
respectively to discuss amendments to the law, Information Minister
Safwat el-Sherif said after a ministerial meeting chaired by
Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
Article 88 of Egypt's constitution requires members of the
judiciary to oversee ballot casting, but the election law passed in
1956 allows civil servants to oversee the polling.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's tiny opposition has long been charging that the
government has relentlessly rigged parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
Minister of State for Parliamentary Affairs Kamal el-Shazli said
the amendments endorsed by Mubarak would require all voting centers
to be overseen by members of the judiciary.
</P>
<P>
They would also require elections scheduled for November this
year to take place "over several days" in order for the judiciary
to be able to monitor around 30,000 voting centers across the
country.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has some 9,000 members of the judiciary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
