<HEADLINE> Iran Dismisses U.S. Court Ruling on Compensation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Wednesday dismissed as
unfounded and politically-motivated a U.S. court ruling that
requires Iran to pay more than 325 million U.S. dollars in
compensation to the families of two Americans killed in a bus
bombing in Israel in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The ruling against Iran is invalid, as the U.S. federal court
lacks the jurisdiction to issue rulings on such issues, according
to
the international law, Foreign Ministry spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi
was quoted by the Islamic Republic News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the ruling is solely based on allegations by the
plaintiffs' lawyers, so it lacks judiciary validity. This "
unfounded" and "politically-motivated" verdict is only catering to
certain anti-Iran groups in the United States, he added.
</P>
<P>
U.S. federal judge Royce Lamberth said in his ruling on Tuesday
that Iran had provided support and resources for the militant
Palestinian group Hamas, who claimed responsibility for the 1996
attack in Tel Aviv. The bombing killed 23 people, including the two
Jewish American students. 
</P>
</TEXT>
