<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel to End Border Violations Soon: U.N. Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 12 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Middle East envoy Terje
Roed-Larsen said Wednesday that the U.N. peacekeepers can be
deployed throughout south Lebanon at the end of this month once
Israel has made required changes of its troops' deployment on the
border.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy here,
Larsen said it was hard to say exactly when the peacekeeping troops
would deploy in south Lebanon "because we are waiting for all
Israeli violations to come to an end."
</P>
<P>
Israel pulled all its forces out of south Lebanon on May 24,
ending its 22-year occupation of the land there. However, the U.N.
Interim Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL) has not deployed in the vacated
areas as Beirut still claims that Israel is violating its
sovereignty at nine points on the border.
</P>
<P>
"We have reached an agreement with the government of Israel on
how to handle that, and we have taken note that the government of
Israel has committed itself to rectify everything by the end of the
month, and I do hope that that will immediately trigger UNIFIL to
deploy throughout the south," Larsen said.
</P>
<P>
There are about 4,500 U.N. peacekeepers currently stationed in
Lebanon. UNIFIL has expected to expand its forces following
Israel's withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Larsen arrived Wednesday for talks with Levy on the border
violations and the dispute seems to be drawing to a close.
</P>
<P>
Larsen said Israel has given its full commitment to make
required changes to the deployment on its border and UNIFIL is
working everyday to establish a line which is clean of any
violations.
</P>
<P>
Levy said that Israel is working in full cooperation with the
United Nations both on the political and military levels and will
make all border adjustments required.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the current list of demands from
Lebanon will be the last one and Beirut will also fulfil its
commitment under U.N. Resolution 425.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister stressed that Israel wants the border to
remain quiet and backs the rehabilitation of south Lebanon helped
by international aid.
</P>
<P>
Levy also emphasized the importance of creating a joint Israel-
Lebanese UNIFIL mechanism for dealing with border related issues.
</P>
<P>
Larsen said work on creating such a mechanism is underway.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the ongoing Camp David summit between Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and U.
S. President Bill Clinton, Levy said it is still too early to say
whether there will be an agreement between Israel and the
Palestinians as both sides remain far apart on their positions.
</P>
<P>
Levy, who refused to accompany Barak to the summit, said both
the Israelis and Palestinians must be ready to compromise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
