<HEADLINE> Mandela Wants Stronger Black Economic Empowerment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Former South African
president Nelson Mandela said on Wednesday that long-term
stability in South Africa was dependent on black economic
empowerment.
</P>
<P>
"Long-term stability also in our political system is dependent
on the success of black economic empowerment through which all
South Africans will feel that they have a stake in the economy,"
Mandela said at a New Economy Investment conference in Sandton in
northern Johannesburg, which was attended by a wide selection of
companies.
</P>
<P>
He said local financial institutions, like all other agencies
of the economy, should work towards greater equity.
</P>
<P>
"Too often we still find that those traditionally excluded from
the fruits of our progress continue to be marginalized," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said the development of small, medium and micro
enterprises was generally recognized to be crucial to job creation
in the country.
</P>
<P>
He said too often small entrepreneurs complained that their
contribution to economic development and job creation was being
stifled by their lack of access to financing.
</P>
<P>
"Similarly, one hears the comment that black economic
empowerment is being impeded by the absence of financing, and the
growing reluctance of the financial sector -- which is still
traditionally dominated and controlled -- to continue investment
in empowerment," he said.
</P>
<P>
While it could be argued that charity began at home, Mandela
added, the call for domestic solidarity would have a far greater
impact, especially when it came to international markets.
</P>
<P>
"If we can harness our domestic energies towards equity, we
shall stand so much stronger as members of the developing world to
argue for equity goals in global affairs," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Asian financial crisis revealed how inter-dependent
world markets were, but it also proved that the vulnerable and the
poor were most hard hit by such global tremors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
