<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Leaders Sign Draft Treaty of African Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOME, July 12 (Xinhua) -- African leaders attending the closing
ceremony of the 36th annual summit of the Organization of African
Unity (OAU) signed here on Wednesday the draft treaty on the
establishment of a closer African Union, taking a decisive step
towards integration.
</P>
<P>
The leaders urged all member states of the OAU to take the
necessary measures for its ratification as soon as possible in
order to ensure its speedy implementation.
</P>
<P>
The Draft Constitutional Act of the African Union will enter
into force after two-thirds of the OAU's 53 member states ratify
it.
</P>
<P>
The African Union will replace the OAU, which was established
on May 25, 1963 in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia, one year after the
document comes into force, according to the draft treaty.
</P>
<P>
The Declaration adopted at the fourth extraordinary summit of
the OAU in Sirte, Libya, on September 9,1999 decided to establish
an African Union to take up the new challenges that confront the
African continent in the light of the social, economic and
political changes taking place in the world, especially the
growing trend of globalization.
</P>
<P>
The objectives of the African Union are to achieve greater
unity and solidarity among the African countries, defend the
sovereignty, territorial integrity and independence of its member
states, accelerate the political and socio-economic integration of
the continent and promote peace, security and stability in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The Assembly of the heads of state and government is the
supreme organ of the African Union and it shall meet at least once
a year.
</P>
<P>
Other organs include the Executive Council of Ministers, the
Pan-African Parliament, the Court of Justice and the financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
Governments which come to power through unconstitutional means
shall not be allowed to participate in the activities of the
African Union.
</P>
<P>
Libyan leader Muamar Gaddafi, who has been advocating the idea
of the United States of Africa, made an emotional speech at the
closing ceremony amidst loud cheers.
</P>
<P>
"Today is a historic day, and the creation of the African Union
will be one of the most important incidents in this century," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He believed that the African Union would unite the African
peoples as one despite of their racial, cultural, language and
religious differences.
</P>
<P>
Togolese President and OAU's Chairman Gnassingbe Eyadema
declared that the continental organization will hold a special
summit next March in Sirte and the 37th annual summit in Lusaka,
Zambia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF Chief Calls for State of Emergency to Combat AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Carol Bellamy, executive
director of the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF), Wednesday
called on the world to declare a state of emergency in the face of
the HIV/AIDS pandemic.
</P>
<P>
"For what is at stake is nothing less than the very survival of
entire country," she said at the launch of UNICEF's "Progress of
Nations 2000" report in Durban, South Africa, where an
international AIDS conference is underway.
</P>
<P>
Describing the pervasive reach of the Human Immuno-deficiency
Virus, Bellamy said: "In parts of Eastern and Southern Africa
whole population groups are being wiped out -- government
officials, professionals, farmers and humanitarian aid workers as
well."
</P>
<P>
UNICEF's 2000 report showed that in 1999 alone an estimated 860,
000 primary school children in sub-Saharan Africa lost their
teachers to AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The virus was threatening the implementation of the Convention
on the Rights of the Child and was an obstacle to achieving the
goals of the World Summit for Children, the report claimed.
</P>
<P>
Bellamy said almost 3.2 million children under the age of 15
had died since the onset of the pandemic, and at current rates
infant mortality would jump 75 percent in the worst affected
countries within a decade.
</P>
<P>
The under-five mortality rate would rise by over 100 percent,
and in addition, nearly 10 million children had lost one or both
parents to AIDS, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The number of AIDS orphans was expected to rise to over 40
million by 2010, with more than 90 percent of them in sub-Saharan
Africa, it said.
</P>
<P>
Bellamy said six people under the age of 24 were infected every
minute -- amounting to 7,000 young people and 1,000 infants daily.
</P>
<P>
She also called on the world to adopt a multi-sectoral approach
in coping with the disease.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that what is required here is the largest
mobilization of resources in history," she said.
</P>
<P>
Governments, world bodies, scientists, civil society and
business have repeatedly been challenged at the conference to join
forces in the battle to curtail the virus, which has infected
about 40 million people.
</P>
<P>
Professor Hoosen Coovadia, AIDS conference chairman and
internationally renowned AIDS expert, agreed with Bellamy's stance.
</P>
<P>
He said South Africa's own leaders had declared war on
apartheid, but had not tackled AIDS with the same energy.
</P>
<P>
The picture was bleak, but there were signs of hope that people,
especially the youth, were changing their sexual behavior, he said.
</P>
<P>
A government study conducted recently found that people between
the ages of 15 and 30 were showing signs for the first time that
they were using condoms regularly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Gets Anti-AIDS Grant From U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The United States National
Institute for Health on Wednesday granted the Medical Research
Council (MRC) of South Africa 19 million U.S. dollars to establish
two new research units to study HIV/AIDS prevention strategies.
</P>
<P>
This is the biggest grant from the U.S. to a South African
research institution, which will contribute to establishing a HIV
vaccine trial unit and a HIV prevention trial unit.
</P>
<P>
The vaccine project is one of the two trials -- the other in
Kenya -- which will concentrate on finding a vaccine suitable for
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Abdool Karim, director of HIV prevention and vaccine
research at the MRC, said: "Both units will ensure that South
Africa stays at the forefront of the global effort to devise and
test HIV vaccines and prevention strategies."
</P>
<P>
Scientists from the University of Natal and Columbia University
in the U.S. will collaborate in the HIV prevention trial unit.
</P>
<P>
So far most of the vaccines have been tested in the U.S. and
Europe.
</P>
<P>
The MRC is the only non-American organization to receive such a
grant. 
</P>
</TEXT>
