<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Foreign Minister Urges for Peace in Africa  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Minister for
Foreign Affairs and International Cooperation Jakaya Kikwete on
Tuesday urged African countries to stop endless and senseless wars
and put more efforts on economic development.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in the National Assembly, the foreign minister said
the conflicts in the African continent are "a big shame and
disgracing."
</P>
<P>
He said there is nobody else to blame for the wars except the
nations themselves, particularly their leaders.
</P>
<P>
"They should sober up and face economic problems rather than
engage in the conflicts," said Kikwete.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that there are some conflicts that are foreign-
influenced, but he insisted that the leaders of those countries
should refuse to "be used for the benefit of other nations".
</P>
<P>
He cited the conflicts in Sierra Leone and Angola and said they
are being "fueled from outside due to the nations' richness in
diamonds."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he also appealed to African leaders to desist from
using force to enter into leadership, saying they are, through
this way, "killing" democracy.
</P>
<P>
He told the parliament that the current conflicts in the
continent and those still being brewed are a big challenge to the
Organization of African Unity (OAU), which held a summit in Lome,
Togo. 
</P>
