<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Putin Urges Keeping Strategic Balance by Keeping ABM Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Vladimir Putin on
Tuesday urged the United States to maintain the balance of
strategic offensive weapons in the world by giving up the planned
creation of a national missile shield and to pool efforts with
Russia against possible threats.
</P>
<P>
Russia proposes to advance from a common initial position,
stands for retaining the level of confidence and the balance of
strategic offensive weapons, reached under the 1972 Anti-Ballistic
Missile (ABM)treaty, Putin told an interview with Russia's ORT
television, Japan's NHK television and the Reuters news agency.
</P>
<P>
He called on Washington to work together with Moscow to "
localize possible threats that could theoretically appear in the
world some day."
</P>
<P>
Russia's proposals have been outlined in statements by the
president "and a number of statements from the Foreign Ministry,"
Putin said. These concern "the creation of a global security
system and a lower level of confrontation between the leading
nuclear powers."
</P>
<P>
He said he is prepared "to begin negotiations (with the U.S.)
on further mutual arms reduction to 1,500 warheads even today."
</P>
<P>
"What can be better for mankind than a lower level of nuclear
threat? We propose to take this path, it is clear and
understandable for everyone, even those who are not experts,"
Putin stressed.
</P>
</TEXT>
