<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New UNICEF Report Details Enormous Impact of AIDS on Youth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Children
's Fund(UNICEF) on Wednesday released a major report detailing the
enormous impact of HIV/AIDS among young people, and said their
efforts would be key to fighting the disease.
</P>
<P>
Released simultaneously in New York, Geneva and Durban, South
Africa, where the 13rd International AIDS Conference is taking
place this week, the Progress of Nations 2000 shows that almost a
third of all people with HIV/AIDS are between the ages of 15 and
24.
</P>
<P>
Every minute, six people under the age of 25 catch HIV, with
girls being more than 50 percent more likely to contract the virus
than boys, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Of particular concern is the fact that young people are not
clear on how to protect themselves from the disease, according to
the report.
</P>
<P>
In a number of countries where AIDS is epidemic, nearly half
of sexually active girls believe they face no risk of contracting
the disease, said the report.
</P>
<P>
 In surveys in 17 countries, over half of adolescents could
not name a single method of protecting themselves against
infection, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report said that young people must be involved in tackling
the AIDS crisis and urged governments to commit to the largest
mobilization of resources in their history and to organized
themselves as if they were fighting a full-blown war of liberation,
with young people in the forefront. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
