<HEADLINE> Russian Duma Chairman Visits Romania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Seleznev said at the meeting that the two countries have good
political relations and must however improve their economic ties.
He also said that the Russian Federation was opened for developing
joint ventures that best guarantee mutual profits.
</P>
<P>
Constantinescu stressed the importance of the Russian
Federation in preserving the European security and the necessity
for cooperation between the two states in achieving regional
stability.
</P>
<P>
A major role is played by the relaunch of the economic
cooperation links, the joint businesses, and the improvement of
the legislative environment and economic incentives, the Romanian
head of state said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that all these are necessary in order to put into
use the whole potential and recoup what was of value in the
bilateral economic relations, given the juridical frame on the
making in the investment domain, namely the investment guarantee
and the avoidance of the double taxation.
</P>
<P>
Resuming negotiations to make the basic Treaty complete is
still a priority on the bilateral agenda, but this Treaty must be
attuned to the sentiment of the two Parliaments, Constantinescu
said.
</P>
<P>
Seleznev heading a delegation of Russian parliamentarians is on
an official visit to Bucharest after having participated in the
9th annual meeting of the OSCE Parliamentary Assembly in Bucharest
over July 6-10. On Tuesday, he met several Romanian officials:
Prime Minister Mugur Isarescu, Foreign Minister Petre Roman,
Senate Chairman Mircea Ionescu Quintus and Chamber of Deputies
Chairman Ion Diaconescu.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held on Wednesday, Seleznev said that the
Russian party wants the basic Treaty with Romania to be ratified
and signed without saying anything about the treasure and the
Ribbentrop-Molotov Pact. "All the differences of opinion existing
between Russia and other countries can be solved by various acts
but not by the basic Treaty," he added.
</P>
<P>
In relation with Romania's intention to join NATO, Seleznev
said that his country was against the enlargement of this
organization,but Romania had the right to opt for the bloc in
which it wishes to be. "We should not want Romania's accession to
NATO to be detrimental to our relations. We don't want to regard
NATO as a rival, but we should really enjoy to have no rival at
our borders.If the Warsaw Treaty expired, NATO should have expired
too," Duma Chairman said.
</P>
<P>
Seleznev also stressed that NATO's intervention in Yugoslavia
was not a good omen and "when the aggression was over" no end was
put to the problems existing over there. 
</P>
