<HEADLINE> U.N. Refugee Agency Seeks $23 Million for Aid to Horn of Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugee (UNHCR) on Wednesday said it needed 23
million U.S. dollars to deal with the humanitarian cost of the
most recent war between Ethiopia and Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
The war has driven nearly 100,000 Eritreans into Sudan,
Djibouti and Yemen and caused massive displacement within Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the agency said it was asking for 13.2 million
to care for internally displaced persons inside Eritrea and to
help those who may initially return to Eritrea from neighboring
countries over the coming months.
</P>
<P>
The remaining 8.6 million is needed for up to 94,000 Eritreans
living in extremely harsh conditions in makeshift camps in
neighboring Sudan since May of this year, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
UNHCR's mobile emergency teams operating in Eritrea and other
relief agencies are braving considerable logistical and
operational odds to help internally displaced persons scattered
throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
 Broad swaths of southern and southwestern Eritrea are
occupied by Ethiopian forces which are unlikely to pull back until
the deployment of peacekeepers from the United Nations and the
Organization of African Unity, in accordance with the agreement
signed by the two countries on June 18, UNHCR said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
