<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Approves Bill Easing Computer Export Controls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate voted Wednesday
to ease export controls on high-performance computers in a bid to
help American companies keep their competitive advantage in the
global market.
</P>
<P>
By a vote of 86-11, the Senate adopted an amendment to the
defense authorization bill that would decrease to 60 days the 180
days Congress has to review changes in administration export rules
on such computers.
</P>
<P>
Supporters of the easing say current controls are ineffective
because they are much stricter than those of foreign competitors.
</P>
<P>
"Today's vote is a big victory for the U.S. high technology
industry and for the jobs and economic growth that this important
industry has generated," said Harry Reid, a Democratic Senator
from Nevada who is one of the sponsors of the amendment.
</P>
<P>
The Senate last March put aside legislation to create a new
process for determining what items with dual commercial and
military uses would come under export controls.
</P>
<P>
The basic export law has not been renewed since 1994, and since
then President Bill Clinton has had to grant export waivers on a
case-by-case basis. Since 1993, Clinton has revised control
requirements for high-performance computers four times, the latest
in January.
</P>
<P>
The House, as part of its Defense Department authorization bill,
has approved the same 60-day review. The Clinton administration
supports a 30-day review period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
