<HEADLINE> Lebanese Labor Union, Political Groups Hold Anti-Government Demonstration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The General Workers Confederation
(GWC) of Lebanon and 10 political groups of the country launched a
demonstration in Beirut Wednesday afternoon to protest against the
government's financial and social policies.
</P>
<P>
The demonstration would be the biggest against the current
government since it was installed 20 months ago, local Al Mustaqbal
newspaper said before the start of the demonstration.
</P>
<P>
The GWC, which groups Lebanon's 350,000-strong labor force, had
called on the demonstrators to assemble at 5 p.m. (1400 GMT) to
converge on the cabinet headquarters when the 16-member cabinet
under Prime Minister Salim Hoss would hold its regular weekly
session.
</P>
<P>
The GWC statement said the peaceful protest was aimed at
demanding sweeping changes to the government's financial and social
policies, a re-adjustment of salaries, a ban on further indirect
taxes and a considerable slash on telephone, water and electricity
bills.
</P>
<P>
Among the 10 political groups also taking part in the protest
are Hezbollah (Party of God) and Amal, the main Shiite Muslim
groups that had spearheaded the resistance against Israel's
occupation of south Lebanon, the Communist Party, the National
Liberal Party and the Lebanese branch of Syria's ruling Baath
party, three right-wing Christian factions -- the Phalange Party,
the National Bloc Party and the National Liberal Party, as well as
Al Jamaa and Al Ahbash, Lebanon's two biggest Sunni Muslim groups.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Salim Hoss said the government would make no move
to stop the demonstration, local newspapers reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said the government was focusing on encouraging foreign
investment in Lebanon "because only investment will get the economy
moving anew."
</P>
<P>
The chambers of commerce, industry and agriculture issued a
statement after its joint meeting Tuesday, warning of an "impending
economic collapse."
</P>
<P>
"Emergency measures have to be taken by the government to check
the breakdown of business outfits before it is too late. Otherwise,
the nation's economy may collapse entirely," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement also called on the government to ensure liquidity
to pump cash into the stagnant markets to revive wholesale demand
as well as commercial, industrial and agricultural businesses.
</P>
<P>
Some 8,000 Lebanese workers joined the unemployment list from
January 1, 1999 to the middle of this year, as compared to a total
of 4,000 workers laid off in 1997 and 1998, As Safir newspaper
reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
