<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Asian Meeting on Urban Governance Concludes in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The three-day South Asian
Conference on Urbanization and Good Urban Governance concluded
here Wednesday with the participants vowing to promote and
facilitate good urban governance by mobilizing optimal
participation of all-level governments and civil society.
</P>
<P>
The South Asian nations "must pay urgent attention to improve
their institutional and managerial capabilities to meet the future
challenges of rapid urbanization", said the Kathmandu Declaration
issued at the conclusion of the conference.
</P>
<P>
The rapid urbanization process has created problems such as
dilapidation of infrastructure, degradation of the environment,
deterioration of the quality and coverage of urban basic services,
exploitation of women and children and the weakening of personal
security", the declaration said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that while one fifth of the population of South
Asian countries lived in urban areas in 1975, the percentage has
increased to 30 percent now and will reach 40 percent in the next
15 years. The growth is among the fastest in the world.
</P>
<P>
To promote good governance and solve these problems, the
declaration urged national governments to give local governments
adequate power and resources to make their governance systems and
mechanisms more participatory, responsive and accountable.
</P>
<P>
The declaration also stressed the importance of regional
cooperation in promoting good urban governance. It called for the
South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) to
include the issue in its agenda and set up a regional urban
observatory to help SAARC countries achieve the objective.
</P>
<P>
The conference, co-organized by Nepali Ministry of Physical
Planning and Works and the U.N. Development Program, explored new
avenues and experiences for capacity building of the local
governments in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
Participating in the conference were about 100 representatives
from the governmental and non-governmental organizations of SAARC
countries including Bhutan, Nepal, the Maldives, Pakistan, India,
Sri Lanka, and Bangladesh. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
