<HEADLINE> Servicemen, Policemen Involved with Deviationist Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Nine servicemen and two
policemen in Malaysia are said to be involved with the
deviationist group Al-Ma'unah, which is responsible for the arms
heist at two army camps in Grik in the northern state of Perak on
July 2.
</P>
<P>
Nine servicemen comprising officers and other ranks found to be
involved with the group are being questioned, Defense Minister
Najib Tun Razak said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The minister however did not say whether all of them are from
the army or other branches of the Malaysian Armed Forces.
</P>
<P>
The nine servicemen are not among the 27 cult members who
surrendered on July 6, he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Najib said he believed other armed forces personnel are also
involved. "We will identify them right to the rank and file," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Bernama news agency quoted Deputy Inspector-General
of Police Mohamad Jamil Johari as saying Wednesday that two police
personnel, one, an officer, are believed to be members of the Al-
Ma'unah group said to have deviated from the true teachings of
Islam.
</P>
<P>
Mohamad Jamil said that an investigation is being conducted to
ascertain the extent of their involvement in the group.
</P>
<P>
"They have not been suspended and no action has yet been taken
against them as we have to investigate whether they have joined
the group just to learn the silat (fight with swords) or have been
deceived into pursuing for the setting up of an unlawful Islamic
state," he was quoted as saying after a function in Serdang.
</P>
<P>
Mohamad Jamil said that the police view such activities
seriously and would take preventive measures before they pose
threats to the country.
</P>
<P>
The police would monitor groups found to display unhealthy
trends, he said, adding, "As such, we will take action if we know
that their activities could pose a threat to national security."
</P>
</TEXT>
