<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lockerbie Trial Adjourned Again After Witness Refusal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAMP ZEIST, Netherlands, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The Lockerbie
trial was adjourned again on Wednesday after a group of witnesses
refused to testify against the two Libyans accused of blowing the
Pan Am flight in December 1988.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the Scottish court on Dutch soil said that the
witnesses from the Mediterranean island state of Malta had refused
to come after quite lengthy negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The court was adjourned until Friday, the spokesman said. The
court was just resumed on Monday after being adjourned for 12 days
to give the prosecution extra time to examine the statements given
by the witnesses listed by the defense team prior to the beginning
of the trial.
</P>
<P>
The Maltese witnesses were summoned to discuss the events
happened at the Luqa airport on Malta, but they refused to give
their names or elaborate in court, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution allege that Abdel Basset Ali al-Megrahi and
Lamen Khalifa Fhimah placed a bomb in a suitcase which was then
placed on an Air Malta jet departing from Luqa on the morning of
December 21, 1988.
</P>
<P>
Later in the day the suitcase was transferred onto the New York-
bound Pan Am Flight 103 that was blown out of the sky over
Lockerbie, killing all 259 people on board and 11 others on the
ground in the Scottish town.
</P>
<P>
The two Libyans went on trial on May 3 before the Scottish
court at Camp Zeist, a former United States air force base in
central Netherlands. They are charged with conspiracy of murder,
and breach of international aircraft safety laws.
</P>
<P>
Al-Megrahi and Fhimah both pleaded innocent to the charges
which carry a maximum life sentence in a Scottish jail.
</P>
<P>
One of the prosecution's principal witnesses is a Libyan
defector who allegedly saw one of the defendants introduce the
suitcase onto the Air Malta flight at Luqa.
</P>
<P>
The trial, that got underway after almost 12 years of
investigation and preparation, was adjourned several times for
both technical and witness reasons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
