<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Relaunches Euro Publicity Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The European Union on Wednesday
relaunched its publicity campaign about the single currency to
facilitate the transition to physical circulation.
</P>
<P>
Pedro Solbes, European Union finance commissioner, said while
kicking off the publicity campaign in Brussels that the campaign
was relaunched due to the fact that the preparation for the
transition to the physical circulation of the single currency is
not adequate.
</P>
<P>
He said that the publicity campaign has two major tasks, one
being to prepare the euro itself and the other being to prepare
the general public.
</P>
<P>
The euro will come out into physical circulation on January 1,
2002, and the citizens in the euro zone countries have to be fully
prepared for the new currency that will replace their national
currencies in the end.
</P>
<P>
The European Union is aiming at preparing the public with
publicity campaigns aimed at both a pre-circulation and dual
circulation periods.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the executive body of the 15-nation
bloc, on Wednesday published for the first time a comprehensive
report on the arrangements of the cash changeovers in the euro
zone countries.
</P>
<P>
The report covered such issues as the end date of the national
currencies and the offer of euro banknotes by ATM teller-machines
in each euro zone member state.
</P>
<P>
The commission said that it had stepped up monitoring the cash
changeover arrangements, was pushing for solutions on any
unresolved issues and was promoting best practices among member
states.
</P>
<P>
Solbes said: "Eighteen months before the euro-day, preparations
for the cash changeover are at a critical stage. Member states
have to reinforce their efforts to ensure that all necessary
decisions and preparations are being made in time in order to
provide certainty to all companies and consumers across the union
and to give them enough time to prepare."
</P>
<P>
Practical aspects of the introduction of euro coins and
banknotes will be discussed on September 8 and 9 during an
informal EU finance ministers council.
</P>
<P>
The single currency was launched in January last year to be
used as accounting units among 11 EU member states that include
Belgium, Germany, Spain, France, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg, the
Netherlands, Austria, Portugal and Finland. Greece joined the
group at the EU summit at Feira, Portugal, last month.
</P>
<P>
Euro coins and banknotes will enter physical circulation
starting on January 1, 2002, while national currencies of the euro
zone member states are to be withdrawn within a period of between
zero day and two months after the euro-day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukrainian Delegation to Visit IMF Headquarters for Credit Resumption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, July 12 (Xinhua) -- An Ukrainian government delegation
will pay a visit on July 22-24 to the headquarters of the
International Monetary Fund in Washington for talks on the
resumption of financing for the country, an official said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The delegation to be led by First Deputy Prime Minister Yuri
Yekhanurov will include many top officials of the government and
the National Bank of Ukraine NBU), in particular, Finance Minister
Igor Mityukov and NBU Chairman Volodymyr Stelmakh, Press Secretary
of the first vice-premier Hennadii Harmash told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the delegation will hold talks with managers
and directors of the IMF on the resumption of crediting under the
Extended Fund Facility (EFF) program, halted in September 1999.
</P>
<P>
The government expects this visit to help solve a number of
unsettled questions in Ukraine-IMF relations, which have been
impeding Ukraine from obtaining foreign credits for almost 10
months.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian government considered that Ukraine has met all
the principle demands of the EFF program, and that the reason
behind delay in the funding is bureaucracy of IMF middle-branch
officials.
</P>
<P>
The IMF mission, which worked in Kiev in June, did not advise
the IMF board of directors to resume funding for Ukraine. They
made a list of 11 preliminary measures the Ukrainian side should
meet first, so that its question would be discussed at the meeting
of the IMF board of directors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
