<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hacker Brought to Justice in Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, July 12 (Xinhua) -- A former employee of an
insurance company in this capital city of central China's Henan
Province has been charged with hacking into the company database
and deleting and revising company data.
</P>
<P>
The defendant, Wang Bo, said he was taking revenge against his
former employer, the Zhengzhou Branch of the China Pacific
Insurance Co. Ltd, when he deleted 1,510 policy records in the
company database, altered the premium and benefit payment
schedules of more than 10,000 policy records, and changed the
company's service telephone number, for he was very unhappy with
his company.
</P>
<P>
As a result of Wang's alterations, the insurance company issued
480 policies containing errors, which "seriously disrupted normal
business order," according to a company spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The district court in Zhengzhou city will hear Wang's case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai to Develop E-Commerce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 12 (Xinhua) -- E-commerce will be a new engine
for the development of trade in Shanghai, vice-mayor Feng Guoqin
said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2005, e-commerce volume is expected to reach 20
billion yuan (about 2.4 billion U.S. dollars), compared with
present 500 million yuan, Feng said.
</P>
<P>
E-commerce, an entirely new method of doing business via the
Internet, is experiencing rapid growth worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Many websites in Shanghai have been actively engaged in e-
commerce, seeking customers who are learning to shop via the
Internet, said Feng, who is in charge of the city's business
affairs.
</P>
<P>
One Shanghai company is sending bottles of mineral water to
customers who send in e-mail orders for the product.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai Cigarettes and Sugar Group Co. has more than 1,300
pieces of merchandise on its website.
</P>
<P>
The M18.com, a comprehensive website, has millions of clients
across the country. The site was launched by a Shanghai-based
international company with millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
Major department stores in the metropolis have joined hands in
developing B2B websites. Banks and airline companies have helped
passengers to order tickets on-line using credit cards.
</P>
<P>
The official said e-commerce can reduce investments in building
shopping centers and increase Shanghai businessmen's
competitiveness with their rivals in other parts of China.
</P>
<P>
Feng acknowledged that e-commerce is facing problems, such as a
lack of regulations and law.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
