<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet Achieves Grain Self-sufficiency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Tibet Autonomous Region on the "roof
of the world" has achieved self-sufficiency in grain production
through decades of effort, a government official said here today.
</P>
<P>
The official of the statistics department of the region said
that the annual grain output in Tibet has exceeded 900,000 tons
and the annual grain per capita has been 360 kg last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the department, the production of grain, edible
oil and meat in Tibet is in balance and the targets for grain,
edible oil and meat production set by the Third Conference on the
Work in Tibet have been reached.
</P>
<P>
With a population of 2.5 million, the Tibet Autonomous Region
mainly produces wheat and highland barley. In 1999, it turned out
922,000 tons of grain and 147,000 tons of meat. The annual meat
per capita reached 60 kg.
</P>
<P>
Due to the unfavorable climate and oxygen deficiency on the
highland, agriculture in Tibet is backward, and in past decades
Tibet has mainly depended on grain shipped from inland areas of
the country.
</P>
<P>
Gyabo, vice-chairman of the Tibet Autonomous Region, said that
in the late 1980s, Tibet needed 170 million kg of grain shipped
from the inland areas annually.
</P>
<P>
The yearly grain load accounted for more than half of the
freight shipping from inland areas to Tibet, and the state had to
allocate more than 300 million yuan for the Tibet-bound grain
shipping expenditure.
</P>
<P>
To stimulate grain production, the region adopted a series of
preferential policies in agriculture tax.
</P>
<P>
A number of grain, edible oil and meat production bases were
established with the development of water conservation projects in
the valleys of the Lhasa River, Nyangqu River and Yarlung Zangbo
River.
</P>
<P>
Of Tibet's 62 projects completed with the aid of the central
government and inland provinces and municipalities, nine involving
agriculture, animal husbandry, forestry and water conservation
have gone into operation, laying a sound foundation for the
sustainable and stable agricultural growth in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Tibet invested more than 3 billion yuan in farming
development and construction projects and improved irrigation
conditions for about 60,000 ha of farmland.
</P>
<P>
Now the irrigation conditions for more than 70 percent of the
farmland in the region have improved.
</P>
<P>
Tibet also popularized science and technology in agricultural
production, including technology for high-yield grain production,
improving cattle breeding and fine seed cultivation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suspects of Major Bus Accident Detained </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Police have taken into custody
four men involved in last Friday's bus accident in southwest China
's Liuzhou city that killed 78 passengers.
</P>
<P>
The four suspects are identified as Pan Yanyang, Pan Tianming,
Peng Changheng and Liu Heping, all temporary workers with the
Liuzhou Utility Maintenance Department.
</P>
<P>
Deng Yuren, a member of the investigation team formed by the
government of the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, made the
announcement at a press conference here today.
</P>
<P>
The investigators said that on the day of the accident, the
four suspects failed to remove cement partitions from the Hudong
Bridge after finishing their maintenance work.
</P>
<P>
That night, a bus of the Liuzhou bus company crashed into the
cement partitions and lost control, plunging into the river 17
meters below. 
</P>
</TEXT>
