<HEADLINE> 15.8 Tons of Narcotics Seized in Southeastern Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Iran said on Wednesday that its
security forces have confiscated 15.8 tons of illicit drugs in the
southeastern province of Sistan and Baluchestan since the beginning
of the current Iranian calendar year (starting March 20).
</P>
<P>
Commander of the provincial security forces Brigadier General
Nasser Shabani said that seven tons of the drugs were discovered in
Zahedan district, the provincial capital, the official Islamic
Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Shabani said that 34 drug-traffickers were arrested and 14
killed in operations during the period, while 22 out of 43 border
routes that could be used for drug shipment in the province have
been sealed off.
</P>
<P>
Over 50 tons of narcotics were seized in the province in 1999,
the official added.
</P>
<P>
Iran is the main transit of drugs from the "Golden Crescent"
overlapping parts of Afghanistan, Iran and Pakistan, to the Gulf
and European countries, despite its effort to crack down on drug
traffickers.
</P>
<P>
It closed down its 725-kilometer borders with Afghanistan on
Tuesday as part of the measures to fight threats to its security,
according to IRNA.
</P>
<P>
The move was taken during a visit by Interior Minister
Abdolvahed Musavi Lari to the eastern parts of the country,
following a sharp rise in criminal cases of robbery, kidnapping,
murder and drug trafficking in the border regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
