<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1 Killed, 25 Injured in Iranian Bus Accident in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 12 (Xinhua) -- An Iranian-registered passenger bus
Wednesday veered off the road and plunged into a ditch in Patnos
town of Agri Province in eastern Turkey bordering Iran, killing one
passenger and injuring 25 others.
</P>
<P>
The passenger bus was on its way back to Iran when the accident
happened, Head Official of Patnos town Ahmet Yurtseven was quoted
by the country's Anatolia News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
Among the 25 injured, 14 were taken to Agri State Hospital while
11 in critical conditions were sent to neighboring Van Province for
treatment, he said.
</P>
<P>
The official said investigation was still under way and the
cause of the accident was not available right now, Anatolia
reported.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has lost more people to traffic accidents than to wars
and devastating earthquakes. The last decade has witnessed an
alarmingly high number of fatal traffic accidents that have claimed
60,000 lives and seriously injured or disabled 1 million people.
</P>
<P>
The main causes are overspeed, carelessness and drivers' lack of
training.
</P>
<P>
The number of traffic accidents usually skyrockets in summertime
and religious holidays as millions of Turks travel around the
country by car.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish parliament recently established a special
commission, aiming to pass a bill reforming traffic laws to curb
traffic accidents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
