<HEADLINE> Pakistani Non-Traditional Items Exports Up in Fiscal 1999-2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's exports of non-
traditional items have witnessed a high growth during the fiscal
year 1999-2000, says the Export Promotion Bureau (EPB) in Karachi
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The government is concentrating on the promotion of non-
traditional items while the EPB has chalked up a plan to further
increase the export of those items which are getting less
attention.
</P>
<P>
The EPB has selected six non-traditional items including
seafood, fruits and vegetables, gems and jewelry, and auto parts
for exports in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
The exports of chemicals and pharmaceuticals registered a sharp
rise of 107 percent to 102.273 million U.S. dollars during 1999-
2000 compared to 49.288 million dollars in 1998-1999.
</P>
<P>
The exports of fruits has registered an increase of 41 percent
to reach 78.405 million dollars during the period, compared to 55.
528 million dollars in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
However, the exports of vegetables sustained a decline of 19
percent, falling from 47.326 million dollars during 1998-1999 to
38.338 million in 1999-2000.
</P>
<P>
The exports of seafood products, despite low international
demand, grew by 13.39 percent to 139.051 million dollars during
1999-2000 compared to 122.631 million dollars in 1998-1999.
</P>
<P>
The exports of embroidery also witnessed an increase of 43.84
percent to 13.357 million dollars during the period under review
compared to 9.286 million dollars during 1998-1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
