<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Creates Largest Property Company in Southeast Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's two leading property
companies, Pidemco Land Limited (Pidemco) and listed DBS Land
Limited (DBSL), signed a merger agreement Wednesday to create the
largest listed real estate company in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Pidemco is one of the largest property groups in Singapore with
total assets of 8.2 billion Singapore dollars (about 4.7 billion U.
S. dollars) and has significant presence overseas with investments
in 24 cities in the world.
</P>
<P>
DBSL is the second largest property company listed on the main
board of the Singapore Exchange (SGX) with a market capitalization
of 3.5 billion Singapore dollars (about two billion U.S. dollars).
With a total assets of 7.5 billion Singapore dollars (about 4.3
billion U.S. dollars), DBSL also has significant operations
spanning in Asia Pacific and Europe.
</P>
<P>
Following the merger, DBSL will be delisted from the SGX and
become a wholly owned subsidiary of the listed new Pidemco with
total assets of approximately 18 billion Singapore dollars (about
10.3 billion U.S. dollars) and a presence in 31 cities and many
countries.
</P>
<P>
Philip Yeo, the current Pidemco chairman who is also the
Chairman of Singapore's Economic Development Board, will serve as
Chairman of the new Pidemco and Hsuan Owynag, the current DBSL
chairman, will hold the position of Deputy Chairman.
</P>
<P>
Liew Mun Leong, current Pidemco President who will be named
President and Chief Executive Officer of the new Pidemco, said "
the increased size is a significant step toward both companies'
vision to become a world-class real estate company where the
achievement of critical mass is an essential factor."
</P>
<P>
The merger is believed to be in line with the economic strategy
adopted by Singapore's government to create world-class companies
to enhance the country's economic competitiveness in the region as
well as in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
