<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola Vows to Stem Illegal Diamond Mining by Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The Angolan government has decided
to reinforce its army in the diamond-rich northeastern provinces
as part of its efforts to crack down on illegal diamond mining by
the rebels of the National Union for the Total Independence of
Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
"After the re-capture of almost all the districts in the
northeastern Lunda-norte and Lunda-Sul provinces, the main target
of the Angolan Armed Forces (FAA) is to fight the guerrilla
actions and the illegal prospecting of diamonds in the region,"
General Sa Miranda, commander of the Angolan Northeastern Military
Front, was quoted as saying by the official news agency Angop here
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The government forces are now intensifying its operations in
Saurimo, capital city of Lunda-Sul Province to tighten siege on
rebels to impede them from getting support from inside and outside
of the country.
</P>
<P>
According to local analysts, the UNITA rebels led by Jonas
Savimbi grabbed resources in the above-mentioned provinces to
sustain their troops and the civil conflicts against the
government troops during the past 26 years.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Angolan rebels led by Savimbi have
accumulated some 4,000 million U.S.dollars from diamond
trafficking during the country's civil war which broke out soon
after the independence of the southwestern African country from
Portugal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
