<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Space Module Goes Into Smooth Work, Says Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The Russian-made service module for
the International Space Station (ISS) launched Wednesday morning
has begun functioning normally in its first orbits around the
earth, said a top Russian expert on the ISS program.
</P>
<P>
All the unfolding elements of the module named "Zvezda" (Star),
such as radio and television antennas and solar batteries, are
operating smoothly, General Designer of the Energiya Aerospace
Corporation Yuri Semyonov told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
Telemetric data received confirmed that the module's
transmitters and receivers are functioning normally, Semyonov said.
</P>
<P>
Russia successfully launched the module into the desired orbit
with a Proton-K rocket from the Baikonur Cosmodrome in Kazakhstan
Wednesday morning. The rocket-booster fired off at 8:56 a.m.
Moscow time (0456 GMT) and put the module into the scheduled orbit
at 9:06 a.m. Moscow time, said an Interfax report.
</P>
<P>
The cargo of the module worth 320 million U.S. dollars will
constitute the living quarters of the ISS. "The launch is crucial
because without this module the further development of the ISS is
impossible," said Alexander Kuznetsov, Deputy Director of the
Russian Space Agency.
</P>
<P>
The Zvezda, a key element of the 60-billion dollar ISS program,
is scheduled to dock by computer on July 26 with two other space
station components, Zarya and Unity, which were launched in 1998.
A three-man team called "zero crew" is on standby in Baikonur to
race into space and make the connection manually in case the
automatic docking fails.
</P>
<P>
Before the July 26 docking, space officials on the ground will
test the control systems and will adjust the orbits of Zarya-Unity
tandem.
</P>
<P>
At the first stage of building the station, a project which
space officials have dubbed one of the most important events in
the history of Russian-U.S. space cooperation, the Russian service
module will make it possible for the crew to operate and control
all the station's systems.
</P>
<P>
Both Russia and the United States have a lot riding on the
success of Zvezda, which will be the heart of the 16-nation space
station project. As well as containing flight controls and the
sewage system, the Zvezda will be a hub for future modules and is
where the crew will sleep.
</P>
<P>
The launch of the 22-ton, 43-foot-long module after over two
years of delays due to Russia's economic woes is a big leap
forward for the ISS project, which also unites the U.S., Canada,
Japan and Europe.
</P>
<P>
Crews will finally have a place to live on board the largest
and costliest space ship ever built. A joint Russian-U.S. crew
could move in as early as October.
</P>
<P>
It will take about 35 space missions before the ISS complex is
complete in 2005. It will then weigh 418 tons, loom seven stories
high and spread over almost an acre of space.
</P>
<P>
It will be visible at night with the naked eye and have about
as much living and working space as a Boeing 747 jumbo jet, said
experts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
