<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Seeks Peace Treaty With Japan Under Prior Pacts, Says Putin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Vladimir Putin
said Wednesday that Moscow is ready to overcome difficulties in
developing ties with Japan and conclude a peace treaty with Tokyo
in the framework of existing bilateral accords.
</P>
<P>
"Russia and Japan should work together on a peace treaty on
the basis of prior accords," said Putin during an interview with
Russia's ORT television, Japan's NHK television and Reuters.
</P>
<P>
If Russia and Japan develop all-encompassing cooperation, the
problems on which the peace treaty depends will stop being a major
factor and straining our relations," the president pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The two countries should work hard on the basis of reached
agreements, he said, noting that he has established "very good
personal relations" with Japanese Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori.
</P>
<P>
"It seems to me that it is most important to be tolerant of
each other, not to rush but, as I have already said, to proceed
from the lawful interests of both sides," Putin said.
</P>
<P>
Japan and Russia are interested in "developing economy,
developing relations in culture and education, using what Japan
has and can share with Russia, using what Russia has and can offer
to Japan," Putin said.
</P>
<P>
"As soon as we take this path together, the problems that now
seem so complex and difficult to solve will stop being of
paramount importance in our relations. They will simply become
secondary matters and certainly be solved," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, the Russian Foreign Ministry announced
that Russian and Japanese leaders will hold a summit meeting in
early September, just before the U.N. Millennium Summit.
</P>
<P>
This agreement was reached at a meeting of Russian Foreign
Minister Igor Ivanov and his Japanese counterpart Wednesday in
Miyazaki, Japan.
</P>
<P>
The exact date for the summit will be decided during the Group-
8 summit slated for late July in Japan's Okinawa, said the
ministry.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers both emphasized that the summit will
become a major step toward building a creative partnership between
Russia and Japan, thus "provide tangible content to the
understanding of the strategic nature of the Russian-Japanese
relations in the modern world," it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
