<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Results of three small experiments in Africa raised hopes
that new AIDS treatments now available only in the world's richest
countries might prove usable for larger, poorer AIDS-infected
populations in many cities of the Third World.
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. President Clinton opened high-stakes talks with
Palestinian and Israeli leaders aimed at settling what he
described as the profound and wrenching questions at the core of
their 52-year conflict.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The Israeli and Palestinian leaders began a summit meeting
at Camp David Tuesday with the far-reaching goal of ending their
52-year-old conflict.
</P>
<P>
-- After 213 years of fighting for the civil rights of blacks,
the African Methodist Episcopal Church took a groundbreaking step
Tuesday night, electing a woman as bishop of the church for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- Clinton pressed Senate leader Lott to set a vote on the
China trade bill, fearing that a delay could push the debate into
the fall campaign season. Separately, the House voted 339-82 to
pass a 75.3-billion-U.S.-dollar farm-spending bill that cuts
Clinton initiatives and drew a veto threat.
</P>
<P>
-- Painwebber agreed to be bought by Swiss banking giant UBS in
a half-cash, half-stock transaction for about 12 billion U.S.
dollars, or 73.50 U.S. dollars a share. 
</P>
