<HEADLINE> Philippines to Send 20 Athletes to Sydney Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' hope of putting an
end to 64 long years of Olympic gold medal drought lies on 20
Sydney-bound national athletes, Philippine Olympic Committee (POC)
President Celso Dayrit said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines is actually sending a 40-member delegation --
composed of 20 athletes and 20 officials -- to the sports meet to
be held in Sydney, Australia this September.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Olympic batch is considered as one of the
smallest delegations the country has ever produced in the world's
biggest sports spectacle.
</P>
<P>
According to Dayrit, 17 athletes have so far qualified and two
or three more are likely to make the list prior to the final
submission of lineups to the Sydney Olympics Organizing Committee.
</P>
<P>
"We are happy and very confident that all our athletes are
raring to go," Dayrit told reporters.
</P>
<P>
But while the athletes' numbers may not be enough to actually
reflect the high hopes of local Olympic offcials, there's no
stopping the POC from talking big-time as far as the Philippines'
gold medal output is concerned.
</P>
<P>
Dayrit, for instance, is optimistic of the delegation's gold
medal chances in boxing and taekwondo where the Philippines is
sending world-caliber bets.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the POC chief predicted a four gold medal haul a
couple of months ago from two sports disciplines alone, a
statement which prompted critics to raise more howlers and
eyebrows on Dayrit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
