<HEADLINE> FIFA to Discuss Principles for Choosing World Cup Host </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The executive committee of the
International Football Federation (FIFA) will discuss new rules
for designating the FIFA World Cup organizer at its next meeting
in August, according to a FIFA press release received here today.
</P>
<P>
Following up on the vote to determine the host association of
the 2006 FIFA World Cup, FIFA President Joseph S. Blatter has
elaborated in a letter to the FIFA Executive Committee on his
suggestions in last month's FIFA News that the system for awarding
the FIFA World Cup needs to be reviewed.
</P>
<P>
In his letter, the FIFA President also referred to his remarks
at the media conference on 6 July following the announcement of
the results of the vote and stressed the importance that FIFA
should not repeatedly grant the World Cup to the same continents
but, on the contrary, should be entrusting its flagship
competition to different confederations in compliance with a
method that has yet to be defined. In particular, he listed
several options:
</P>
<P>
-- By rotating from continent to continent;
</P>
<P>
-- By limiting the number of candidates per continent;
</P>
<P>
-- By simultaneously designating the organizers of two
consecutive World Cups;
</P>
<P>
-- Either by combining all three principles or by adopting
other principles that would lead to the same goal.
</P>
<P>
A letter from the African Football Confederation (CAF) echoing
the same sentiments has been received by FIFA in the meantime.
</P>
<P>
The agenda of the next meeting of the FIFA Executive Committee
on August 3 will therefore include an item under which there is to
be an open discussion of a variety of options enabling FIFA to
adopt a new policy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
