<HEADLINE> Shanghai Sees Rise in Minimum Income Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The minimum income level of
Shanghai residents this year has risen to 280 yuan (about 33.7 U.S.
dollars) from 120 yuan a month in 1993, according to mayor Xu
Kuangdi.
</P>
<P>
"The Shanghai municipal government's primary goal is to improve
people's living standards," Xu said at a recent banquet for a
mayor's forum sponsored by the Asian Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
He said Shanghai is setting up a system to guarantee people's
basic living conditions, in which the government would provide
financial support to people who are living below the poverty line.
</P>
<P>
The city is also improving its social security system, he said.
The government will guarantee the basic living conditions of those
who have lost their jobs and help them to get re-employed.
</P>
<P>
He said some 588,000 laid-off workers have found jobs again
with assistance from employment centers in the city.
</P>
<P>
The city also helped 30,000 people who had difficulties in
finding jobs get re-employed, he said.
</P>
<P>
In order to guarantee people's education and medical care
rights, Xu said, Shanghai has provided medical aid to more than 10,
000 people over the past three years and 105 million yuan to cash-
strapped students in 1999.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
