<HEADLINE> China to Hold Nationwide Production Safety Review </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese State Council has
decided to immediately hold a nationwide check on production
safety to curb the surging number of accidents here, vice-premier
Wu Bangguo said here today.
</P>
<P>
In a televised national conference, Wu said enterprises failing
to pass the examination would face stern sanctions, including
suspension or even closure of business.
</P>
<P>
The vice-premier criticized local officials and enterprise
managers for ignoring production safety rules and documents from
the central government.
</P>
<P>
He also held supervision and law enforcement agencies
responsible for the rising rate of production-related accidents in
China, saying that some agencies did not fulfill their duties.
</P>
<P>
Wu stressed that authorities must not be lenient in dealing
with serious accidents.
</P>
<P>
Penalties must be imposed not only on those who are directly
responsible, but also on the leaders of institutions and
supervising authorities, he said.
</P>
<P>
The conference was held in the wake of a dozen serious
accidents that have occurred in China in the last two weeks,
leading to hundreds of deaths and huge economic losses.
</P>
<P>
Sheng Huaren, the minister in charge of the State Economic and
Trade Commission briefed participants on the production safety
situation in the first half of the year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
