<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey to Have Two Days Off Amid Torrid Weather </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The Turkish government will close
all offices on Thursday and Friday to beat the intensified heat
wave, the country's Anatolia News Agency reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The government said in a circular that the temperatures will
keep soaring in the upcoming days which may severely threaten human
health.
</P>
<P>
The decision was approved by Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit
following an application from the Health Ministry on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The circular warned administrators to take the necessary
measures to prevent interruption in services and keep a minimum
number of personnel who will run the basic services.
</P>
<P>
According to a weather forecast issued by the State Meteorology
Office earlier this week, the country will have record-breaking
high temperatures on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The highest temperatures will be 40 degrees Celsius in Ankara;
41 degrees Celsius in Antalya, on the southern coast of the
Mediterranean Sea; and 43 degrees Celsius in Diyarbakir, in the
country's southeast.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the death toll of the heat wave that has
enveloped the country since the beginning of last week has risen to
13 after two people died from the heat wave on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A 51-year-old man fainted in the heat at a train station in the
western Aydin province and died on the way to hospital.
</P>
<P>
In a village of Bursa province, west Turkey, an old man, aged
80, died at home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
