<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK's Jobless Figure Hits 20-year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The jobless total in Britain has
fallen to a 20-year low as the Government celebrates a huge
increase in employment levels.
</P>
<P>
Employment has grown by more than a million since the Labor
government came to power in 1997 to reach a new rate of 74.6
percent, the best figure recorded. The unemployment rate was 3.8
percent, the lowest rate since 1975.
</P>
<P>
Employment has increased by 126,000 over the three months to
May, by 346,000 over the year and by over a million since Spring
1997, according to the figures that the Office for National
Statistics (ONS) released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The broader measure of unemployment, the International Labor
Organization (ILO) unemployment, fell even faster, by 47,000, in
the period from March to May to 1.67 million, a rate of 5.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
"It is possible for the first time in a generation to talk
about full employment in Britain," said UK's prime minister Tony
Blair.
</P>
<P>
However, despite the healthy set of figures, the data also
revealed the fall in manufacturing jobs, down by 95,000 over the
past year to fall below 4 million.
</P>
<P>
The figures from ONS also show average earnings increased by 4.
6 percent in the year to May, down by 0.5 percent on April's
figure, largely because of falling bonus payments in a number of
industries including finance, recreation and retail. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
