<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Wise Men Nominated to Scrutinize Austria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Three men including a former
Finnish president were nominated Wednesday as the wise men to
scrutinize the human rights record of Austria.
</P>
<P>
The nomination of former Finnish president Martti Ahtisaari,
former Spanish Foreign Minister Marcelino Oreja and German
professor Jochen Frowein was pronounced in Brussels by Romano
Prodi, president of the European Commission, the executive body of
the European Union.
</P>
<P>
The nomination of the three wise men, made by the European
Court of Human Rights, was seen as an outlet for lifting the
political sanctions imposed by 14 EU member states on Austria
after the country incorporated the far-right Freedom Party into
the governing coalition.
</P>
<P>
The court named the three wise men in alphabetical order,
suggesting that it had not nominated any of the trio to chair the
panel.
</P>
<P>
The Strasbourg-based court issued a written statement saying
that the trio would report directly to the nation that is holding
the six-month rotating presidency of the 15-nation bloc, which is
now France.
</P>
<P>
The court did not set any deadline as for when the trio has to
complete their scrutiny and hand in their report, though some
expected their report to come out before the planned Austrian
plebiscite so as to shun a further political row within the union.
</P>
<P>
Disappointed that no deadline was set for the handing-in of the
wise men's report, the Austrian coalition parties agreed last week
to hold a non-binding referendum on its relations with the
European Union and the plebiscite is scheduled to be held either
on October 29 or November 26 this year.
</P>
<P>
Austrian Foreign Minister Benita Ferrero-Waldner said in
Brussels on Monday that the referendum might never happen and the
European Union should deflect the plebiscite by lifting the
sanctions before any vote takes place.
</P>
<P>
Austrian Federal Chancellor Wolfgang Schussel said in Brussels
on Wednesday that his country would cooperate with the wise men in
their scrutinization and that he believed their report would turn
out to be a clean sheet of human rights records on the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Department-Store Operator Seeks Court-Mandated Restructuring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Sogo Co., a financially troubled
Japanese department store chain, on Wednesday filed with the Tokyo
District Court for protection from creditors, aiming to seek
rehabilitation, said Sogo President Kyoichi Yamada.
</P>
<P>
The court accepted the chain's request and issued an order for
protection of Sogo's assets so the company can proceed with
restructuring under a new law designed to let firms facing an
imminent collapse jump-start rehabilitation, Yamada told a press
conference.
</P>
<P>
Sogo has debts totaling some 1.87 trillion yen (17.4 billion U.
S. dollars), one of the largest amounts shouldered by a company
seeking court protection from creditors, financial sources said.
</P>
<P>
In line with its management restructuring plan drawn up in
April, Sogo has been calling on creditor banks to give up claims
on loans worth a total of 630 billion yen, (5.9 billion dollars),
an amount necessary to enable the company to seek restructuring on
its own.
</P>
<P>
The amount includes 97 billion yen (902 million dollars) in
loans held by Japan's state-run Deposit Insurance Corp. (DIC).
</P>
<P>
The DIC, along with other creditor banks, decided in June to
forgive the loans, a decision that has sparked public criticism
that the move represents an effective bailout of a private company
by the government.
</P>
<P>
Yamada said the ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) on
Tuesday asked his company to seriously reconsider its request to
the DIC.
</P>
<P>
Sogo's executive board decided to meet the request and give up
restructuring on its own, instead opting for the court-mandated
rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
Sogo, with outlets in Japan, as well as in major Asian cities,
actively expanded its department store network in recent years.
The expansion, however, entailed massive interest-bearing debts,
which, coupled with sluggish consumer spending, troubled the
retailer financially. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
