<HEADLINE> Thaw Seen in Belgium-Austrian Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 12 (Xinhua) -- A slight thaw was seen here in
Brussels on Wednesday when Belgium invited the Austrian ambassador
to participate in the country's national celebration.
</P>
<P>
It was a tentative move by Belgium, one of the hard-line
opponents toward Austria's incorporation of its far-right Freedom
Party into the governing coalition.
</P>
<P>
Belgium joined 13 other European Union member states in the
political isolation imposed on Austria after the coalition was
sworn in on February 4.
</P>
<P>
At the height of the joint sanction moves, even Belgian school
children called off their planned skiing vacations in the Austrian
mountains and the then Freedom Party chief Joerg Haider, the man
in the center of the political dispute, called off his trip to
Brussels to attend the European Union's regional committee meeting.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman of the Belgian foreign minister, however, said
that the invitation was not a loosen-up on the front of the joint
sanctions, according to a local television report.
</P>
<P>
He explained that all the other EU member states had invited
Austrian ambassadors to their respective national holiday
celebrations.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian National Day falls on July 21. 
</P>
