<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment Allowed in West-East Gas Pipeline Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investors will be allowed
to control the main stake in West-East Natural Gas Transportation
Pipeline Project and to contribute funding to other urban gas
pipeline construction.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Guobao, vice-minister in charge of the State Development
Planning Commission (SDPC), told a press conference today that the
new policy fully demonstrates the central government's
determination to open wider to the outside and to push its entry
into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
The state will not approve solely state-owned investment in the
pipeline project, which is estimated to cost 40 billion yuan, in a
bid to make foreign-controlled investment possible, with no
ceiling set for their share-holding percentage, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The West-East Natural Gas Transportation Pipeline Project is
the most ambitious ever undertaken by the central government in
its effort to developing the vast western areas.
</P>
<P>
In addition to favorable policies given to infrastructure
construction, the pipeline project also enjoys favorable policies
earmarked for the westward strategy, including fee cuts and
exemptions in mineral exploration and mining, tax-free imports of
related equipment, and land-use.
</P>
<P>
The Tarim Basin of the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region is
estimated to have 8.39 trillion cubic meters of natural gas
resources, 494.1 billion of which have been verified, sufficient
for 12 billion cubic meters of annual gas transportation in the
early stage of the project.
</P>
<P>
Proven gas reserves are expected to reach one trillion in the
next decade, a guarantee for gas supply for 30 years and a
precondition for 20 billion cubic meters of gas transportation in
the future, said Ma Fucai, general manager of China Petroleum (
Group) Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the pipeline is scheduled to start next year
and be completed in 2003, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
