<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Refuses to Intervene in Peso Movement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Despite the peso's continued slide,
the Philippine government said Wednesday that it will maintain its
stand not to interfere in the market, as it remains confident that
the currency can recover soon.
</P>
<P>
Rafael Buenaventura, governor of the Central Bank of the
Philippines, issued this statement after several sectors called
for government intervention when the peso's value fell to a 30-
month low on Tuesday, nearing the 45 pesos to one U.S. dollar mark.
</P>
<P>
"If we see speculative plays we'll intervene. So far we haven't
seen any need to intervene," Buenaventura said in a radio
interview.
</P>
<P>
He also said the government is eyeing a plan to tap the long-
term peso market for debt servicing instead of using dollars.
</P>
<P>
"I suggested to the Secretary of Finance that if there is
liquidity in the system we should not borrow everything in dollars
but go to the long-term peso market. The central bank holds 160
billion pesos (4 billion dollars) in overnight money from banks,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Buenaventura also laughed off claims that the peso dive is a
sign that the country will plunge into a crisis similar to the one
it experienced during the 1997 Asian financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, he noted, interest rates jumped up to 16 percent,
while inflation was at 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
Citing economic indicators for this year, Buenaventura said
interest rates are now at nine percent, while inflation is less
than four percent
</P>
<P>
Buenaventura also said the central bank now has ample dollar
reserves of 16 billion dollar, compared to much less when
President Joseph Estrada took over in 1998.
</P>
<P>
"The peso will correct itself. We only have to keep up with
other currencies," he said.
</P>
<P>
Buenaventura warned traders against engaging in currency
speculation, which may only backfire on them, as what happened to
speculators three years ago.
</P>
<P>
"Speculators in 1997 got burned when they bought dollars at 47
pesos to one dollar but the peso strengthened to 41 pesos to one
dollar," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
