<HEADLINE> China to Speed Up Distance Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 12 (Xinhua) -- China plans to build more
information expressways to facilitate its burgeoning distance
education, an official with the Ministry of Education said here.
</P>
<P>
Most municipalities and provinces will open high-speed
transmission portals by the end of this year, said Zhang Yaoxue,
director of the Science and Technology Department of the Education
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
China Education and Research Network (CERNET) has already
linked over 70 cities involving three million users in some 700
universities and science and research units, according to Zhang.
</P>
<P>
To raise the speed of the network, five 155-megabyte-per-second
information highways linking Beijing and other five cities have
been put in use on a trial basis.
</P>
<P>
He said that China is speeding up the improvement of its
exiting satellite TV education network, and the project is
expected to be completed in October.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Education has recently issued policies to
supervise the development of distance education in China.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that the ministry will encourage more universities
to take part in long-distance education in the near future.
</P>
</TEXT>
