<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Monitors Land Use with Satellite Remote Sensing Tech </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The land use situation in China's
large cities is being monitored by watchful eyes in the sky.
</P>
<P>
China is employing satellite remote sensing technology to
effectively check the occupation of arable land and help
strengthen the administration of land resources, according to the
Ministry of Land and Resources.
</P>
<P>
An exhibition held by the ministry here today revealed that the
land use situations in 66 large cities with populations over 500,
000, including Beijing and Shanghai, were watched over by
satellite between Oct. 1998 through Oct. 1999.
</P>
<P>
Data based on monitoring from satellites developed by the
United States and France showed that 348,000 mu (25,600 hectares)
of cultivated land in the 66 cities were occupied by mines,
factories, railways, highways and other urban construction
projects last year.
</P>
<P>
The monitoring results also showed that some cities were making
false land use reports last year, and they subsequently were
forced to shut down the illegal land use projects according to
land use laws.
</P>
<P>
The ministry will set up a nationwide land use remote sensing
monitoring network in the coming three years, with monitoring of
key cities to be an annual event, and will publish yearly reports
on urban land use.
</P>
<P>
In addition, radar technology will be introduced to monitor
south and southwest China where optical satellite data cannot meet
monitoring requirements because of harsh weather conditions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
