<HEADLINE> Vice-Premier Meets Taiwan's Delegation New Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-premier Qian Qichen
met here today with a delegation, headed by Feng Hu-hsiang, from
Taiwan's New Party.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Qian said he appreciated the New Party's
agreement with the consensus made in 1992 between the mainland's
Association for Relations Across the Taiwan Straits (ARATS) and
Taiwan's Straits Exchange Foundation (SEF) that "both sides of the
straits stick to the One-China principle."
</P>
<P>
The vice-premier said the resumption of contact and talks
between the ARATS and the SEF will be beneficial to the
development of cross-Straits relations, the objection to "Taiwan
Independence", and the protection of rights and interests of
Chinese people on both sides of the Straits.
</P>
<P>
Qian, who is also a member of the Political Bureau of the
Communist Party of China (CPC) Central Committee, said the
resumption of dialogue along with exchanges of mail service, trade
and air and shipping services, known as the "three direct links,"
are the common wishes of Chinese people on both sides of the
Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
The Taiwan delegation arrived in Beijing on July 9 at the
invitation of the ARATS. 
</P>
