<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF Warns India on Spread of AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Erma Manoncourt, deputy director of the UNICEF Program for
India, said, "it is estimated that some 3.5 million people are
infected with HIV/AIDS in India. In two states, Maharashtra and
Manipur, over one percent of the population is infected."
</P>
<P>
"We are still far from the scenario that we see in Africa where
in some villages and cities, upto 30 percent of the population is
infected. But the pattern is familiar," she added.
</P>
<P>
Manoncourt, who released the UNICEF report "Progress of Nations
2000" (PON) here as part of the global launch, said that the
document focuses on four issues which includes spread of HIV/AIDS,
malnutrition, immunization and exploitation of children.
</P>
<P>
She said, "and all the four issues are very relevant to India
as the country hosts the highest number of people with HIV/AIDS in
the world, the highest number of malnourished children, the
highest number of polio cases and the highest number of working
children." 
</P>
</TEXT>
