<BODY>
<HEADLINE> About 30 Injured in Quake in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 12 (Xinhua) -- About 30 persons were injured in
an earthquake measuring 5.1 on the Richter Scale which shook West
Java, Indonesia, on Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
According to the Geophysics and Meteorology Body, the quake
occurred at 08:10 a.m. local time (01:10 GMT). The quake centered
at 6.9 degrees southern latitude and 106.9 degrees eastern
longitude, about 100 kilometers south of Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that hundreds of people in Jakarta, Bandung (
capital of West Java) and Sukabumi (a town near the epicenter)
fled their homes and offices.
</P>
<P>
"It was very strong. Everyone ran out of their houses afraid,"
a housewife in Sukabumi said.
</P>
<P>
The Antara News Agency reported that 257 houses were badly
destroyed and 348 others slightly damaged in Sukabumi regency.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's quake comes only a month after a strong 7.3
magnitude quake shook Bengkulu in West Sumatra, killing 130
persons and leaving thousands homeless. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
