<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda's Population to Hit 25 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's population is expected to
hit 25 million by 2005, a sharp increase from 16.7 million in 1991,
Population Secretariat of Ugandan Finance and Economic Planning
Ministry told Xinhua Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's population now registering at 22.5 million grows at a
rate of 2.9 percent annually, one of the highest growth rate in
sub-Saharan Africa, said the secretariat.
</P>
<P>
According to Minister of Finance Gerald Ssendaula, a big
population is not a problem, what cause a problem is the quality
of the people that make up the population.
</P>
<P>
The minister said, however, that a high population growth rate
would undermine economic growth rate.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that the population will have grown to 32.5
million by the year of 2015, almost double what it was in 1991,
not withstanding the impact of HIV/AIDS and malaria which are the
biggest killer diseases in the east Africa country, according to
the secretariat.
</P>
<P>
Uganda family planning policy allows couples to decide on how
many children to have and when to have them, according to
Ssendaula.
</P>
<P>
However, Acting Director Population secretariat Charles
Zirarema called upon Ugandans to strategically plan for their
families. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Experiences Erratic Economic Growth in Past Decade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe has
said the country's Gross Domestic Product (GDP) growth has been
highly erratic over the past decade due to drought, macro-economic
imbalances and falling investment and export performance.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said in its economic highlights released here
Wednesday that macro-economic imbalances had been manifested in
high inflation and interest rates which had affected investment
and savings.
</P>
<P>
It said per capita growth had been declining over the past
decade as a result. The trends in per capita income showed a
steady decline in living standards.
</P>
<P>
Investment fell from a peak of 22.6 percent of GDP in 1993 to
14.5 percent by the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
"Low economic activity has been evidenced by marked decline in
manufacturing. Agriculture has managed to maintain steady growth
though at low levels," it said.
</P>
<P>
"The contribution of manufacturing to GDP has declined
consistently from 20.5 percent in 1990 to 15 percent by 1999," the
bank said. "Contributions from agriculture rose from 14.8 percent
to 16.3 percent during the same period."
</P>
<P>
The contribution from mining to GDP had declined from about 4
percent in 1990 to 3 percent in 1999 against the background of
falling international mineral prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF Calls for "War of Liberation" Against HIV/AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Nations must commit to the "largest
mobilization of resources in their history" as if they were
fighting "a full-blown war of liberation," if they hope to defeat
AIDS, the disease with young people in the forefront, the United
Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF) said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
HIV/AIDS infects six people under the age of 24 every minute,
according to a new UNICEF report, the Progress of Nations 2000,
detailing the enormous impact of HIV/AIDS among young people.
</P>
<P>
"HIV/AIDS constitutes the greatest threat many societies have
ever faced," said UNICEF Executive Director Carol Bellamy on the
occasion of the publication of the report.
</P>
<P>
"Unfortunately, in many ways it has been a hidden enemy, aided
and abetted by a general reluctance to acknowledge its strength
and our own vulnerability. Thus we have not confronted AIDS with
the full force we are capable of," she said.
</P>
<P>
Major findings from the UNICEF report include:
</P>
<P>
-- Almost a third of all people with HIV/AIDS are between the
ages of 15 and 24, a total of some 10 million young people;
</P>
<P>
-- Girls and young women are more than 50 percent more likely
to contract HIV than boys and young men;
</P>
<P>
-- And in 1999 alone, an estimated 860,000 primary school
children in sub-Saharan Africa lost their teachers to AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The report also finds that in several countries, almost half of
all girls aged 15-19 do not know that a person who looks healthy
can be infected with HIV and transmit it to others; in a number of
countries where AIDS is epidemic, nearly half of sexually active
girls aged 15-19 believe they face no risk of contracting the
disease; and in surveys in 17 countries, over half of adolescents
could not name a single method of protecting themselves against
HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
"Virtually every society understands what it means to wage a
struggle for liberation," the UNICEF chief said, noting that the
concept has particular resonance in Africa. "It means mobilizing
every available resource; it means involving men and women on an
equal basis; it means accepting the vital role to be played by
young people; and it means sparing no effort and brooking no
diversions until all of society is liberated." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Switzerland, EU to Begin New Round of Bilateral Negotiations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Switzerland and the European Union
(EU) will start a new round of negotiations on further bilateral
agreements later this year, Swiss Foreign Minister Joseph Deiss
announced Tuesday after a visit to Brussels.
</P>
<P>
He and EU Commissioner for Foreign Relations Chris Patten said
expert-level talks would begin in fall. Patten restated that tax
evasion would be high on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
Switzerland, for its part, is seeking new areas for bilateral
agreements such as the media, statistics and education, following
the ratification of seven accords which are due to come into
effect next January.
</P>
<P>
Patten said the European Commission would give the go-ahead to
negotiations this week. One of the most controversial issues is
likely to be the EU's demand for non-member countries, including
Switzerland, to signal their willingness to cooperate with an
agreement compelling them to report the assets of non-residents.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the need for balance in bilateral talks, Deiss said
Switzerland had no desire to be seen as a haven for tax exiles,
but wanted to retain banking secrecy.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed Switzerland's interest in broadening
negotiations to include security and asylum policies.
</P>
<P>
At their 45-minute meeting on Tuesday, they reviewed the
ratification process for the seven accords between Switzerland and
the EU, which Swiss voters approved in a referendum on May 21.
Patten said the accords were beneficial to both sides, and urged
individual EU states to accept them as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral agreements are supposed to come into force on
January 1, 2001, once they have been approved by the parliaments
of all 15 EU member states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Cracks Down on Fake Cigarettes  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 12 (Xinhua) -- China is increasing its efforts to
stub out production and sale of fake cigarettes to secure tax
income and protect the consumers' interests, according to the
State Tobacco Monopoly Administration (STMA).
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the STMA show that in the first half of this
year, the country's law enforcement officers dealt with 100,000
cigarette counterfeit cases, closing down 1,500 illegal cigarette
factories and confiscated 3.1 billion counterfeited cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
In March and April, the STMA and several other departments
jointly launched a large-scale campaign in Henan and Guangdong.
Three large illegal factories in Shaanxi, Heilongjiang and Guizhou
were closed down.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the state tightened control over the production and
use of cigarette paper and closed down 26 mills that turned out
substandard cigarette paper during the first half of this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shenzhen B-share Market Up Slightly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The Shenzhen B-share market inched
up 0.20 points, or 0.18 percent, to 110.99 at the close.
</P>
<P>
Turnover was 29.78 million HK dollars, 10.58 million HK dollars
or 26.21 percent more than Tuesday's total, according to Beijing-
based online financial advisory company Homeway.
</P>
<P>
There was little change in today's positive bias as the market
took a modest gain in early morning before resuming its upward
correction pattern. There was little enthusiasm among investors as
they showed caution without knowing exactly if the earnings season
might create a negative stir.
</P>
<P>
Gainers beat losers by 31 to 18, with 6 unchanged.
</P>
<P>
ST Lionda Hold rose 2.29 percent to 1.38 HK dollars, while
Health Mineral added 2.64 percent to 3.50 HK dollars.
</P>
<P>
ST Great Ocean dropped 2.15 percent to 0.91 HK dollars, while
Sez Real Estate slipped 1.94 percent to 2.53 HK dollars.
</P>
<P>
The market is trying to recover, but is still challenged by
sellers. Overall it persists in mixed trading while some minor
gains are likely to be scored amid prolonged cautious sentiment,
Homeway analysts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
