<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Under the threat of Knesset (Parliament) legislation, the
Israel Defense Forces (IDF) announced Tuesday it is cutting the 36-
month mandatory military service for men by four months, beginning
with those drafted in August 2001.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, IDF Manpower Chief Yehuda Segev said
conscription for women will be lengthened by three months to 24
months.
</P>
<P>
The IDF began considering the cuts after the Knesset notified it
last summer that it must reassess its manpower needs, as the region
moves away from the era of large conventional armies.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Israel's two chief rabbis, Yisrael Lau and Eliahu Bakshi-
Doran, had told Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak before his
departure to Camp David that they will not oppose transfer of
control over Rachel's Tomb, Joseph's Tomb, and even the Tomb of the
Patriarchs, to the Palestinians, as long as appropriate measures
are taken to guarantee access, prayer rights and security for Jews
at the holy sites.
</P>
<P>
Neither the halakah (Jewish Law) nor tradition, they said,
requires Jewish sovereignty over graves, including the graves of
the religious pantheon.
</P>
<P>
This is substantial support for the expected IDF withdrawal from
the remaining territories in Hebron, Bethlehem and Nablus in an
agreement with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. President Bill Clinton opened a three-way summit with
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat at Camp David, Maryland on Tuesday. They are to strive for
an agreement on all of the tough final-status issues, including
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"The two leaders face profound and wrenching questions," Clinton
had told reporters on the White House lawn before leaving for the
summit. "Both leaders feel the weight of history but both, I
believe, recognize this is a moment in history which they can
seize."
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Clinton's bilateral
meetings with Arafat and Barak lasted an hour and 50 minutes
respectively. The three then held a 30-minute trilateral meeting.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Israel's Supreme Court is to hand down a dramatic reading of
the verdict in the appeal of former Shas leader Aryeh Deri
Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Deri appealed his conviction by the lower court on charges of
accepting a bribe, breach of faith, and aggravated fraud, and his
sentence of four years in jail and a NIS 250,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
The appeal was heard by a three-judge panel over a period of 18
days from the end of January to the middle of February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
