<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Israeli Minister Sentenced to Three Years in Jail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Israel's Supreme Court decided
Wednesday to uphold the bribery conviction of former Interior
Minister Arye Deri of the ultra-Orthodox Shas party, and to
sentence him to a three-year prison term starting on August 31.
</P>
<P>
The verdict was handed down after the Supreme Court partially
accepted Deri's appeal against the four-year sentence imposed on
him last March by the Jerusalem District Court.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court canceled a number of the clauses of which Deri
was convicted, but upheld the bribery conviction.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem District Court convicted Deri, the country's
youngest interior minister in history and former Shas party leader,
of taking bribes totalling 155,000 U.S. dollars from three friends
and co-defendants - Moshe and Aryeh Weinberg and Yom Tov Rubin, as
well as fraud and breach of trust.
</P>
<P>
The conviction was delivered on March 17, 1999 following a trial
that lasted five years. A three-judge panel ruled unanimously that
Deri pocketed the money over a period of five years from 1985 to
1989 in return for channelling state funds to the Weinberg-Rubin
yeshiva.
</P>
<P>
On April 14, 1999, Deri was sentenced to four years in prison
and fined 250,000 shekels (about 62,500 U.S. dollars) or another 10
months in prison in lieu of the fine.
</P>
<P>
The court also ruled that the count of bribery constituted moral
turpitude, meaning that if Deri's appeal is rejected, he will not
be able to run for public office for 10 years after completing his
prison term.
</P>
<P>
The sentence caused a furor in Shas's constituency, which
revered the charismatic young politician and one of the country's
most powerful people. Six weeks later, Shas won 17 seats in the
Knesset (Parliament) elections, up from 10 three years earlier. The
party thus rose to the status of the third largest parliamentary
grouping after the Labor Party and the Likud.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court decided to reduce the prison term for two
reasons: the suffering caused to Deri's family due to the prolonged
legal proceedings and the extended investigation, which lasted 10
years.
</P>
<P>
Scores of Shas supporters gathered around the Supreme Court in
Jerusalem on Wednesday morning, waiting for the court decision on
Deri's appeal. The police reinforced their presence in the area.
</P>
<P>
Deri said, upon leaving the Supreme Court after the decision was
read, that he receives the ruling with love.
</P>
<P>
Under the Israeli Basic Law, Deri will not be barred from
running for the Knesset if he chooses to do so. The law bans only
someone convicted of a crime against state security from running
for office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila, Pyongyang Forge Diplomatic Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The Republic of the Philippines and
the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) signed a joint
communique here Wednesday formally establishing diplomatic
relations.
</P>
<P>
The joint communique said that the governments of the
Philippines and the DPRK, guided by the principles of the United
Nations Charter and the generally accepted principles of
international law, have agreed to establish diplomatic relations
between the two countries at the ambassadorial level as from the
date of signing of the communique.
</P>
<P>
These principles include respect for domestic laws, national
sovereignty and territorial integrity, mutual respect for
international agreements to which both countries are parties, non-
interference in the internal affairs of states, and equality and
mutual respect, according to the joint communique.
</P>
<P>
The governments of the two countries are also committed to
develop friendly and cooperative relations between their two
countries, said the joint communique, signed by Philippine Foreign
Secretary Domingo Siazon and DPRK's Ambassador to Thailand Jo In
Chol.
</P>
<P>
Jo arrived here Tuesday night for a five-day official visit to
the Philippines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
