<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Count Reaches 123 in Manila Landslide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The death count in the Payatas
garbage dump landslide that occurred Monday morning in Quezon City,
Metro Manila has risen to 123 as of 5:00 p.m. Wednesday, said the
Philippine government.
</P>
<P>
The National Disaster Coordinating Council (NDCC) said 300
families or 998 persons have been evacuated to safe places from
the dumpsite.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-eight people were pulled out of the rubble alive after
the tragedy happened. The last survivor was found at 9:00 a.m.
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
More than 600 personnel from the Armed Forces of the
Philippines, the Philippine National Police and some non-
governmental organizations are still undertaking the retrieval
operations.
</P>
<P>
Retrieval operations were hampered by rain and aggravated by
the combined stench of garbage and decomposing bodies still
entombed in the place. The operations were also hampered by lack
of lime and insecticides.
</P>
<P>
The bodies were placed in cadaver bags and taken to the
basketball court built in the dumpsite. Vehicles from two funeral
parlors bring the bodies to their morgues.
</P>
<P>
The NDCC refrained from issuing an official estimate of missing
persons for lack of accurate source. The authorities, however,
earlier put the figure between 400 and 3,000.
</P>
<P>
Authorities said the search and rescue operations may last for
weeks and the death toll may continue to rise.
</P>
<P>
Ismael Mathay, mayor of Quezon City, said earlier that more
than 100 shanties were buried in the landslide in Payatas dumpsite
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
It was also the day of the failed transport strike and classes
in Quezon city were suspended, accounted by Mathay as the reason
why many of the casualties were children of school age.
</P>
<P>
Due to a week of continuous monsoon rains, the tons of garbage
must have loosened which resulted in its erosion and eventually
became a landslide, said Mathay.
</P>
<P>
There were about 50,000 people residing in Payatas. The open
dumpsite was scheduled to be closed in October 1999, but the
closure was held back for lack of an alternative disposal site for
Quezon City's more than 700 tons of daily garbage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
