<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Takes Tight Measures for Work Permits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
introduced strict procedures for applications seeking work permits
in the country to curb the influx of illegal foreigners, Principal
Immigration Officer H. T. Ndiema has said.
</P>
<P>
The official newspaper Kenya Times Wednesday quoted Ndiema as
saying his department has unearthed a syndicate that presented
false information to get work permits for foreigners without any
academic or technical qualification.
</P>
<P>
Ndiena has directed the members of the Federation of Kenya
Employers to first verify qualifications of employees before
making any moves to assist them acquire the permits.
</P>
<P>
He warned that any employer or employee found to have given
false information or documents would be prosecuted and deported in
accordance with the provisions of the law.
</P>
<P>
Ndiena noted that his government's policy encourages employers
to give priority to Kenya citizens when employment opportunities
arise, saying the hiring of foreign employees should be restricted
to areas where the skills are not available locally.
</P>
<P>
As the country's economic growth is declining, Kenya registers
an unemployment rate of 25 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing Jet Deliveries Back On Track </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Boeing Co., the world's
largest aircraft maker, announced Tuesday it delivered 167
commercial jets in the second quarter, more than double its output
in the first quarter when it suffered through a 40-day engineers'
strike, according to a news release of the aircraft giant.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter, it delivered just 75 jets, compared to
125 planned and 148 delivered in the same period of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Boeing's total delivery of 242 planes as of June 30 put it in a
position to meet its goal of 490 deliveries by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
"As promised, by the end of the second quarter, we have
essentially recovered from the strike," Chief Executive Phil
Condit said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The 167 second-quarter deliveries included 102 of Boeing's best-
selling 737 narrowbodies, plus 18 narrowbody 757s, 13 widebody 767
s and 17 widebody 777s.
</P>
<P>
Boeing Tuesday rose 1 3/4 to 44 1/2 U.S. dollars a share on the
New York Stock Exchange, their best level since February 3.
</P>
<P>
The Society of Professional Engineering Employees in Aerospace
(SPEEA), representing Boeing's engineers and technical workers,
rejected a Boeing contract on February 9, triggering a walkout by
18,000 workers. Boeing and the workers eventually reached an
agreement and the workers came back on March 20.
</P>
<P>
The rapid production recovery underscored the strength of
Boeing's assembly lines, even as it continues to cut jobs and
dispose of non-core businesses including some parts-making
operations, Wall Street analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Clearly the company did a good job getting its act together on
deliveries in the second quarter," said Joe Nadol, an analyst at
Donaldson Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette. "But I'm sure it still has a way to
go before it completely recovers from the strike in more
qualitative ways, including employee morale."
</P>
<P>
Last year, European rival Airbus Industrie surpassed Boeing in
commercial aircraft orders with 476 to the American company's 391.
As of June 30 this year, Boeing had announced orders for 322
passenger jets, compared with 234 for Airbus.
</P>
<P>
Airbus delivered 145 jets in the first six months of 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Luxembourg Tops World Per-Capita GDP List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Luxembourg topped the 1999 world'
s list for per-capita gross domestic product in terms of
purchasing power standards, a local journal reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The journal European Report quoted the statistical bureau of
the European Union (EU) as listing Luxembourg with 38,840 U.S.
dollars per person, up from 35,500 dollars a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The United States came second on the list with 32,710 dollars
per person while Switzerland was third with 27,190 dollars per
person.
</P>
<P>
Norway ranked fourth, compared with the developed countries and
the EU member states, with 26,560 dollars, followed by Canada (
with 25,200 dollars), Denmark (25,000 dollars), the Netherlands (
23,830 dollars), Ireland (23,630 dollars), Austria (23,580 dollars)
, Belgium (23,440 dollars), Australia (23,180 dollars), Japan (22,
870 dollars), Germany (22,710 dollars), Sweden (21,600 dollars),
Britain (21,570 dollars), Finland and Italy (both with 21,160
dollars) and France (20,860 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Spain, Portugal and Greece ended up at the lower end of the
list with 17,320, 15,940 and 14,200 dollars per person
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation European Union averaged a per-capita GDP in 1999
at 21,110 dollars while the 11-nation euro zone was 70 dollars
more at 21,180 per person.
</P>
<P>
The gross domestic product growth in volume terms in the EU
rose by 2.3 percent last year, slightly less than the 2.7-percent
growth posted in 1998. Yet 10 of the EU member states exceeded the
average growth of 2.3 percent. Ireland, for six years on end,
produced the highest GDP growth inside the union with 8.3 percent
compared with 8.9 percent in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
