<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan, U.S. Suspend Talks on NTT Row Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Negotiators from Japan and the
United States again suspended talks over the interconnection fees
charged by Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp. (NTT) shortly
after they resumed the negotiations Wednesday morning as the U.S.
side rejected a compromise proposal submitted by Japan.
</P>
<P>
Japan and the U.S. failed to narrow differences on the NTT
charges during their two-day working-level talks, which first
bogged down on Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
Although Tokyo expected its compromise proposal would lead to
the settlement of the long-standing bilateral dispute with
Washington, it was compelled to consider an additional proposal,
Japanese government officials said.
</P>
<P>
It may take some time for the two sides to resume the talks as
Japanese negotiators are facing strong opposition from the ruling
Liberal Democratic Party against making a further compromise, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
Washington on Tuesday rejected a concession by Tokyo to shorten
the period required to achieve a 22.5-percent reduction in the
phone hook-up charges NTT levies on other carriers from the
earlier proposed four years.
</P>
<P>
Japanese officials said that the U.S. side apparently did not
budge from its demand made in previous talks in late March that
the NTT reduce the interconnection rates by 22.5 percent in two
years and then swiftly reduce them further by a total of 41.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
Japan and the U.S. resumed working-level talks Monday in a bid
to solve the biggest trade row before the Group of Eight (G-8)
summit, which will be held July 21-23 in Okinawa Prefecture, Japan.
</P>
</TEXT>
