<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Launches Module for International Space Station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The rocket-booster fired off at 8:56 a.m. Moscow time (0556 GMT)
Wednesday morning from the Baikonur cosmodrome in Kazakhstan and
put the module into the scheduled orbit at 9:06 a.m. Moscow time (
0606 GMT), said an Interfax report.
</P>
<P>
Zvezda is scheduled to dock with the Zarya-Unity tandem of the
ISS on July 26. During the two weeks before the launch, the
control systems will be thoroughly tested and the orbits of both
Zarya and the tandem, which has been spaceborne since December
1998, will be adjusted.
</P>
<P>
Zvezda is a key element of the ISS. At the first stage of
building the station it will make it possible for the crew to
operate and control all the station's systems, notably those
responsible for altitude control, stabilization, orbit correction
and other functions needed for a manned mission and for the
continued construction of the station.
</P>
<P>
If everything goes as planned, the first long-term crew will
fly to the ISS in late October or early November. It will include
crew commander William Shepherd, Soyuz-TM commander Yuri Gidzenko
and engineer Sergei Krikalyov. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
