<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Expects Record Temperatures in Store </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The Turkish State Meteorology Office
has rung a warning bell against extraordinary record-breaking
temperatures throughout the country on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Minister of State responsible for the State Meteorology
Office, Ramazan Mirzaoglu, cautioned earlier this week that
temperatures will start rising again from July 12 and reach the
hottest levels across Turkey on July 13.
</P>
<P>
The highest temperatures on July 13 will be 40 Celsius in the
capital of Ankara; 41 Celsius in Antalya, on the southern coast of
the Mediterranean Sea; and 43 Celsius in Diyarbakir, in the
country's southeast.
</P>
<P>
He added the unusual high temperatures will start to go down on
July 14, giving way to rainy weather over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, the Health Minister, Osman Durmus,
Tuesday sent a circular note to governors of 81 provinces to
enforce an afternoon siesta, which is aimed at avoiding the edge of
the heat wave.
</P>
<P>
He asked government offices to shut down from 1100 a.m. to 0400
p.m. local time when the sun is at its most ferocious period.
</P>
<P>
Hot weather alarm has been sounded one after another since an
intense heat wave intruded into Turkey from the beginning of last
week, which has played havoc with production and people's daily
life.
</P>
<P>
According to a bulletin released by the Forest Ministry's fire-
fighting center, a total of 9,094 hectares of land has been burned
thusfar in forest fires.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said many more precaution measures will be taken in
the next three days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
