<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Camp David Summit Unlikely to Make Miracle: UAE Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The ongoing U.S.-hosted peace
talks between the Palestinians and Israel at Camp David is unlikely
to make any breakthrough after Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
announced his five "NOs" in the talks, commented newspapers in the
United Arab Emirates (UAE) Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The Camp David summit started yesterday (Tuesday) amid
pessimism from the Palestinians following Barak's five 'NOs' and
after the Israeli opposition threatened to topple him if he offers
what they see as concessions," the Abu Dhabi-based Al Ittihad
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
"The summit," it added, "will not reach a positive outcome
unless it tackles the declaration of a Palestinian state with its
capital in Jerusalem, besides finding a suitable solution for the
problem of (Palestinian) refugees."
</P>
<P>
The paper urged all parties involved to avoid applying pressure
in order to make a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
At Camp David, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak, with U.S. President Bill Clinton's
mediations, are expected to seek agreements on issues such as the
status of Jerusalem, the Jewish settlements, the fate of
Palestinian refugees and borders.
</P>
<P>
Camp David is a secluded U.S. presidential retreat near
Washington where Egyptian and Israeli leaders clinched their
historic peace deal in the 1970s, the first one between the Jewish
state and an Arab country.
</P>
<P>
The Dubai-based Arabic-language daily Al Bayan also cast doubts
on the chances of success for the summit.
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinians are left with no other choice but to stand
firm in the face of pressure they will meet from both American and
Israeli sides," stressed the paper.
</P>
<P>
Any concessions made by the Palestinians will be considered as
legitimate rights of the Israelis and they will ask more, it added.
The Sharjah-based Al Khaleej daily called on the Palestinians not
to budge an inch from their demands, reminding them that other Arab
countries fully reclaim their territories occupied by Israel.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt (was) returned the whole Sinai following Camp David
(summit) in 1978, Jordan succeeded in demarcating its borders with
Israel following the Wadi Araba accord, Lebanon (was) returned its
territories in the south thanks to its heroic resistance and Syria
insists on returning the whole Golan heights," the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Based on such facts, the Palestinians should stress in the
negotiations that Palestine should be returned to the Palestinians
at least on the basis of borders recognized before the 1967 Arab-
Israeli war, the paper added.
</P>
<P>
"Red lines respect those who draw them and prevent any one from
crossing them. Palestinians should make it clear that no further
concessions are to be made." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
