<HEADLINE> Philippine Stocks End Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Share prices in the Philippine
Stock Exchange ended lower Wednesday, first time this July,
dragged by the peso weakness.
</P>
<P>
The 30-company Phisix, the market's main index, fell 8.51
points to close at 1554.57. The broader all-shares index closed
marginally higher by 64 of a point to 666.79.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1.04 billion shares worth some 22.57 million U.S.
dollars changed hands Wednesday from 625.56 million shares worth
some 18.47 million dollars on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the continued weakness of the local currency has
discouraged investors to trade in the market.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine peso fell sharply against the U.S. dollar on
Tuesday, hitting a 30-month intraday low of 45.15 before bounced
back and ended at 44.82.
</P>
<P>
Others said the country's political situation, including the
war in Mindanao, has further weighed down market sentiment.
</P>
</TEXT>
