<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Essential Medicines to Deplete in Major Hospitals in Zimbabwe: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Essential medicines in all major
Zimbabwean hospitals are expected to run out in the coming month
unless the government secures foreign currency to buy drugs, The
Herald newspaper reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"In all the major hospitals, we are only left with a month's
supply of medicine, a situation that could become critical if we
do not get foreign currency within the next few weeks," Timothy
Stamps, Minister for Health and Child Welfare was quoted as saying
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Drugs that are in short supply include all vaccines, morphine
and quinine. Basics such as bandages, gloves and syringes are also
running short, making the operations of the hospitals very
difficult.
</P>
<P>
Stamps said while hospitals could purchase medicine from any
supplier, they were failing to do so because they had no foreign
currency either.
</P>
<P>
In the affected hospitals the situation is now desperate, with
patients in some cases being asked to pay for their own drugs, the
minister noted.
</P>
<P>
Since last November, Zimbabwe's foreign currency reserves have
been severely depleted, resulting in the current fuel, power and
imported raw materials shortages, which have negatively impacted
on production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
