<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Curbs Sugar Price Hike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian government is
trying hard to stabilize sugar prices after the adjustment of fuel
price one week ago.
</P>
<P>
The measures taken by the government include distributing sugar
in rations through district authorities in Addis Ababa and through
the Whole Sale and Retail Trade Enterprise in the states.
</P>
<P>
Recent sugar hoarding by a few businessmen engaged in sugar
distribution has resulted in a drastic sugar price hike, said an
official with the state-owned Ethiopian Sugar Industry Support
Center Company on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The state sugar price has not changed with the lowest price
remaining at 400 birr (about 48.7 U.S. dollars) for 100 kilograms,
he said.
</P>
<P>
But, sugar is sold in the market of the capital city at six
birr (about 73 cents) a one kilogram.
</P>
<P>
To stabilize sugar price in the country, the sugar authority
has supplied the market with 50,000 tons of sugar, an amount that
was beyond the plan set for this year, the official said.
</P>
<P>
On July 4, the Ethiopian government announced a raise of prices
for diesel, kerosene and petroleum in an adjustment prompted by
the high cost of crude oil on the international market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
