<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Famine Situation Remain Tense: UN Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The famine situation in
Ethiopia remains tense despite donations from the international
communities, a senior U.N. official said.
</P>
<P>
Carolyn McAskie, visiting Emergency Relief Coordinator of the
UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs, on Tuesday
called on donor nations to continue making contribution to drought-
affected Ethiopians.
</P>
<P>
The number of famine victims in Ethiopia has come up to some 10
million from 8 million, according to the UN official.
</P>
<P>
Except for the drought-affected people, the needy people also
include hundreds of thousands of displaced people who became
homeless since the start of Ethio-Eritrean border conflict in May
1998.
</P>
<P>
McAskie indicated that transportation work has become a key to
help famine victims in Ethiopia, saying 140 additional vehicles to
transport relief food will be made available.
</P>
<P>
About 800,000 tons of relief food have been pledged by donor
countries so far, said Manuel Aranda da Silva, UN Regional
Humanitarian Coordinator for the Drought in the Horn of Africa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G-8 Foreign Ministers Kick off Meeting in Southwestern Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Ministers from the Group of
Eight (G-8) began their two-day meeting in the southwestern
Japanese city of Miyazaki Wednesday afternoon in preparation for
the G-8 summit in Okinawa Prefecture later this month, the Kyodo
News reported.
</P>
<P>
The eight ministers are expected to issue a joint statement and
a comprehensive action plan for preventing conflicts early
Thursday afternoon to wrap up their discussions.
</P>
<P>
The statement will also focus on disarmament and nuclear
nonproliferation, U.N. reforms, fight against international
organized crime and terrorism, the environment and regional
security issues.
</P>
<P>
The two documents will serve as a blueprint for political and
security discussions at the Okinawa summit, slated for July 21-23.
</P>
<P>
The statement will commit the G-8 ministers to following up on
the action plan to comprehensively deal with a "full spectrum" of
problems with regard to conflicts, Kyodo quoted a senior G-8
official as saying.
</P>
<P>
The plan will cover states or areas vulnerable to conflict as
well as those in the midst of conflict and those dealing with its
aftermath.
</P>
<P>
It will include five key measures: tightening controls on
diamond trading to stem arms purchases in such war-torn African
countries as Sierra Leone, pressing countries to stop recruiting
children as soldiers, promoting measures to eradicate poverty,
helping nations establish and train civilian police, and
strengthening regulations on exports of small arms to strife-torn
areas.
</P>
<P>
The statement outlines calls for maximizing efforts to realize
U.N. reforms, including an overhaul of the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
It also contains commitments from Moscow and Washington to
quickly implement the second Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty (
START II) and conclude START III. The foreign ministers will
promise to seek an early implementation of the Comprehensive Test
Ban Treaty on nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
On regional security issues, the statement underlines G-8
support for dialogue between the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea (DPRK) and South Korea in the wake of the first-ever inter-
Korean summit, which was held last month in Pyongyang, the capital
of the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
The ministers are expected to spell out a special statement
supporting the Mideast peace summit when they hold a joint
conference Thursday after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright is absent from the
meeting to focus on the U.S.-hosted Middle East peace summit which
opened Tuesday. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott is
attending the G-8 gathering in Albright's place.
</P>
<P>
The G-8 countries are Britain, Canada, France, Germany, Italy,
Japan, the United States and Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Continue to Fall in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices continued falling in
Tokyo Wednesday, reflecting uncertainty over Japan's monetary
policy.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 162.23 points, or 0.93
percent, from Tuesday's close to end at 17,342.13.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, dropped 6.56 points, or 0.41 percent, to 1,
604.40.
</P>
<P>
Investors adjusted positions ahead of a Friday lecture by Bank
of Japan (BOJ) Governor Masaru Hayami and the central bank's
Policy Board meeting next Monday, a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
Hayami was reported as saying Monday in Switzerland that the
Japanese economy is now strong enough to handle a rise in interest
rates, stirring speculation that the BOJ will lift its hyper-easy
monetary policy at the policy-setting meeting.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's decline in New York's Nasdaq composite index was
another factor weighing on Tokyo share prices, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Several high-priced information technology (IT) issues were
damaged by the weakness in Nasdaq, leading the Nikkei index
sharply lower, they said.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section grew to 778.49 million shares
from Tuesday's 723.33 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Showa Electric Wire &AMP; Cable was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
Drugmakers, glass makers and retailers marked sharp declines,
while the real estate, marine transportation and mining sectors
drew buying.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers overwhelmed
gainers 817 to 459, with 118 issues remaining unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
