<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 27 Websites Licensed to Pilot E-advertising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-seven out of the
approximately 15,000 registered websites in China have been chosen
to pilot on-line advertising, an official with the State
Administration of Industry and Commerce (SAIC) announced today.
</P>
<P>
The lucky websites, including www.sohu.com, www.netease.net
and etang.com, are selected for being "well-established" and all
of them are registered in Beijing, Shanghai and Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
Electronic advertising has become a "magnet" for advertisers
seeking market opportunities for its low cost, rapid distribution
and extensive dissemination, said Wang Jinjie, vice director of
SAIC's Advertisement Supervision and Management Department.
</P>
<P>
It has been learned that none of China's current websites that
post advertisements online has obtained government approval, and
problems have occurred from time to time in Internet advertising.
</P>
<P>
To protect the rights and interests of consumers, and
standardize the e-advertising market, SAIC plans to put on-line
advertising under a licence system as advertising on other media,
Wang said.
</P>
<P>
"There should be market access conditions for Internet
advertising firms, and advertisement content should be regulated
accordingly," he added.
</P>
<P>
SAIC has granted Internet ad permits to websites hoping that
they could help explore an effective management and supervision
mechanism for domestic e-advertising.
</P>
<P>
"This doesn't mean that we have given them any privileges.
Instead, we require them to abide by the advertisement rules and
regulations and have their content examined when posting ad for
special commodities, " Wang stressed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
