<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Accelerate Land Redistribution Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The land redistribution and
resettlement program in Zimbabwe is set to resume on a full scale
this Friday, with 160 farms having been set aside for the exercise.
</P>
<P>
Nathan Shamuyarira, Secretary for Information and Publicity of
the ruling Zimbabwe African National Union-Patriotic Front (Zanu-
pf), said Tuesday nigh that at least 20 farms in each of the eight
provinces had been acquired for resettlement and some war veterans
and land-hungry villagers occupying farms will be moved to the
newly acquired farms in the process.
</P>
<P>
"The acquisition notices are being served on the occupants of
each of the designated farms that have not been contested by the
owners," he said.
</P>
<P>
In all, 804 farms have been designated and all the ex-
combatants and peasants who have occupied certain farms will be
required to move from those farms to the newly acquired farms,
where they will be given land and settled permanently, said
Shamuyarira.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean government has said that the land redistribution
program has been very slow and time had come for the national
problem to be solved once and for all.
</P>
<P>
War veterans have said they will not leave the farms they
occupied unless the government provides them with land. The
government envisages to transfer more than 5 million hectares of
land over the next five years to resettle some 150,000 families.
</P>
</TEXT>
