<HEADLINE> Kenya Launches Oil Exploration  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
contracted a British company to explore oil in three of the 19
zones curved for the search in the country, the East African
Standard newspaper reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Energy Minister Francis Masakhalia and three
representatives of the British Star Petroleum signed an agreement
on the exploration here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Star Petroleum is granted eight years to
carry out the studies and drill six wells in the zones covering an
area of 34,893 square kilometers in Lamu and Kwale districts in
southeastern Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The agreement allows Star Petroleum to use its own capital to
carry out the survey and recover the money upon discovering the
oil products.
</P>
<P>
Peter Taylor, director of the British company, said Star
Petroleum would spend more than 300 million U.S. dollars on the
project for the first two years.
</P>
<P>
According to Masakhalia, more than 40 percent of Kenya's
foreign exchange earnings was being spent on importing petroleum
products. 
