<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Launches War on Rebels in Northern Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The European Union parliament has
passed a resolution calling on EU member states to ban the
operations of a rebel group based in southern Sudan fighting
against the Ugandan government.
</P>
<P>
The resolution called on individual EU member states to condemn
and ban operations of Lord's Resistance Army (LRA) and travel of
its representatives within the EU and between the EU and non-EU
nations, the New Vision daily reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It condemned the LRA's continued abduction of children in
northern Uganda and the use of the children in armed combat,
saying it is a violation of UN conventions and the international
humanitarian law.
</P>
<P>
Sudan has been asked to stop supporting the LRA and to
cooperate in the immediate and unconditional release of all
abducted children as stipulated in the Nairobi Peace Accord signed
by leaders of Sudan and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
It said Sudan should consider the abduction of children as a
humanitarian issue and separate it from the larger political
issues in the region.
</P>
<P>
The resolution said Sudan should allow free access by
humanitarian organizations such as the United Nations Children's
Funds to the LRA camps to ascertain the identities of the abducted
children and ensure their safe return to home.
</P>
<P>
The parliament said 14,000 children, some as young as seven
years old, in northern Uganda, particularly in Gulu and Kitgum
districts, had been abducted to Sudan since 1986. It said about 5,
000 children had since returned or escaped and thousands remain
unaccounted for. 
</P>
</TEXT>
