<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Internet Ad Spending Increases in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Spending on Internet
advertising has increased 54 percent from January to June of 2000,
said a report released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to AdZone, a U.S. company tracking Internet
advertising activity data, Internet ad spending rose from 818
million U.S. dollars in January to 1.26 billion dollars in June.
</P>
<P>
In June, the top 10 brands alone spent 367 million dollars,
with Real Networks, a leader in media delivery on the Internet,
leading all others at 103 million dollars. Film.com was a distant
second at 69 million dollars. AOL lead the top spending sites of
June at 65 million dollars in revenues, with Yahoo following at 46
million dollars and eBay at 32 million dollars. Yahoo, Microsoft,
Lycos and American Online remained the top revenue generating Web
site networks in June.
</P>
<P>
AdZone tracks advertising on more than 1,000 Web sites that
comprise more than 95 percent of all Internet advertising revenue
from banners, text ads, keywords, links, button pop-ups,
interstitials and hover text. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Airlines to Cut Fares in Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Most U.S. airlines said
Tuesday they will cut fares by about 25 percent into December to
ensure that the strong traffic levels seen in recent months will
continue into what is typically a slower fall travel season,
according to reports reaching here Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
Discount carrier Southwest Airlines cut round-trip fares to a
maximum of 218 U.S. dollars, with even lower fares for flights on
Tuesday, Wednesday and Saturday, intra-California travel or
flights between Florida and many of its locations. The Southwest
sale is for travel between August 14 and December 9, and tickets
must be purchased by July 27.
</P>
<P>
US Airways Group Inc., the nation's sixth-largest airline,
announced a fare cut of about 25 percent on travel during off-peak
hours through December 15 in the United States, Canada and the
Caribbean. Tickets would have to be purchased by July 21 and at
least 14 days prior to departure.
</P>
<P>
Other airlines, including the world's largest carrier the
United Airlines, No. 4 U.S. carrier Northwest Airlines Corp. and
No. 5 Continental Airlines Inc., said they would match the US
Airways fare sale.
</P>
<P>
Airlines typically have instituted fare sales in the fall, to
attract travelers during the slow season between Labor Day and the
end of year holidays.
</P>
<P>
But airline analysts said they are not terribly worried about
overall revenue drop because the deadline for ticket purchase
rules out many business passengers who pay the top dollar for
seats.
</P>
<P>
"It's not as if the entire airplane is for sale," said Jim
Higgins, analyst with Donaldson Lufkin and Jenrette Securities. He
pointed out that airfares have risen steadily this year in the
face of rising fuel prices and strong demand for seats.
</P>
<P>
Higgins and other analysts said these kinds of seasonal sales
were bound to happen and were fully factored into revenue and
earnings forecasts. 
</P>
