<HEADLINE> New Zealand PM May Miss South Pacific Forum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 12 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Prime Minister
Helen Clark may avoid this year's South Pacific Forum meeting
rather than having to shake hands with Fijian coup leader George
Speight.
</P>
<P>
The latest reports indicate Speight may be appointed Fiji's
prime minister Thursday and it's likely he would attend the forum
meeting in Kiribati from October 28 to 31.
</P>
<P>
A Wellington-based newspaper quoted the New Zealand prime
minister as saying Wednesday that she is reserving all her options,
including not going to the meeting if it is likely Speight or one
of his cohorts would be there.
</P>
<P>
The Evening Post also quoted her as saying that it is
extraordinary that Speight seems likely to be appointed Fiji's
prime minister by Fiji's Great Council of Chiefs Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"How can Fiji expect to have any credibility in the eyes of the
international community when a man who commits criminal and
terrorist acts ... ends up getting into a position of influence
like that," Clark said.
</P>
<P>
She said it would be too unpleasant to have to meet Speight at
the forum meeting. She also signaled New Zealand now needs to
completely rethink its foreign policy in the South Pacific as a
response to the Fiji coup, violence in the Solomon Islands,
political assassination in Samoa and other events. 
</P>
