<HEADLINE> Foreign Trade Reported Rise in Shandong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Foreign trade which were declared at
coastal ports in east China's Shandong Province surpassed more
than 32 million tons of cargoes from January to May this year, a
56 percent rise on a yearly basis.
</P>
<P>
In breakdown, imports were 17.88 million tons, up 65 percent,
and exports were 14.25 million tons, up 47 percent.
</P>
<P>
The number of containers handled at local ports reached 907,000
TEUs during the five-month period, rising 34 percent on 1999 level.
</P>
<P>
Imports of grain reached 1.15 million tons, four times the
figure of the same 1999 period, the largest growth rate among all
local imports.
</P>
<P>
Exports of iron and steel rose 210 percent on the 1999 figure
to 1.26 million tons during the five-month period, the largest
growth rate among all local exports.
</P>
<P>
More than 355,600 tourists came to and left Shandong during the
first five months of this year, a rise of 22 percent on 1999
figure. 
</P>
