<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Current Account Surplus Falls in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Japan's current account surplus fell
in May by 18.2 percent from a year earlier to 840.2 billion yen (7.
8 billion U.S. dollars), down for the first time in four months,
the Japanese Finance Ministry said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The decline in the surplus came as a surge in imports exceeded
a rise in exports of the country, the ministry said in a
preliminary report.
</P>
<P>
Exports increased 8.1 percent to 3,703 billion yen (34.3
billion dollars) while imports expanded 20.5 percent to 2,979.6
billion yen (27.6 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The ministry said the surplus in goods and services trade
slided 36 percent to 318 billion yen (2.9 billion dollars), adding
that the merchandise trade surplus also slowed 24.1 percent to 723.
4 billion yen (6.7 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The current account balance represents the difference between a
country's income from foreign sources and foreign obligations
payable, excluding net capital investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
