<HEADLINE> British Power Company Leases Canadian Nuclear Power Facility </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Ontario Power Generation Tuesday
unveiled a deal of 625 million Canadian dollars (about 422 million
U.S. dollars) for Britain's largest power generator to lease
Canada's largest nuclear facility.
</P>
<P>
Under the 18-year deal, British Energy will operate Canada's
Bruce nuclear power station in southwestern Ontario through a new
entity called Bruce Power Partnership.
</P>
<P>
The deal is aimed to be the first step toward privatization of
Ontario's debt-laden energy sector by the Canadian side. Ontario
Power Generation has agreed to reduce its share of power
generating capacity in the province to no more than 35 percent
within 10 years.
</P>
<P>
To gain the legal status of operating Canada's Bruce nuclear
power station, British Energy has yet to apply for an operating
license from the Canadian Nuclear Safety Commission and must
subject the deal to Canada's Nuclear Safety and Control Act.
</P>
<P>
"The safe operation of the Bruce nuclear generating station is
our top priority," Ontario Energy Minister Jim wilson has once
said.
</P>
<P>
Located 250 kilometers northwest of Toronto on the shore of
Lake Huron, the aging Bruce facility includes eight CANDU nuclear
reactors, of which only four are producing electricity by using
uranium fuel and heavy water. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
