<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Toll Rises to 108 in Manila Landslide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The number of casualties in the
Payatas garbage dump landslide that occurred Monday morning in
Quezon City, Metro Manila has climbed up to 108, the National
Disaster Coordinating Council (NDCC) said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The NDCC said in a report that as of 8:00 a.m. Wednesday, 297
families or 847 persons have been evacuated.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, more than 600 personnel from the Armed Forces of the
Philippines, the Philippine National Police and some non-
governmental organizations are still undertaking the rescue
operations.
</P>
<P>
The NDCC refrained from issuing an official estimate of missing
persons for lack of accurate source. The authorities, however,
earlier put the figure between 400 and 3,000.
</P>
<P>
Rescuers said it may take three to four days for them to pick
through the collapsed area of the dump and the death toll may
continue to rise.
</P>
<P>
Ismael Mathay, mayor of Quezon City, said earlier that more
than 500 families were affected and 100 shanties were buried in
the landslide in Payatas dumpsite.
</P>
<P>
Due to a week of continuous monsoon rains, the tons of garbage
must have loosened which resulted in its erosion and eventually
became a landslide, said Mathay.
</P>
<P>
There were about 50,000 people residing in Payatas. The open
dumpsite was scheduled to be closed in October 1999, but the
closure was held back for lack of an alternative disposal site for
Quezon City's more than 700 tons of daily garbage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Baht Slides to 9-Month Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The Thai baht dipped to a nine-
month low Tuesday, breaking 40 baht to the U.S. dollar in the
afternoon trade before gaining ground to end 39.95 to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the baht followed other regional currencies lower
against the dollar, with the Philippine peso and the Indonesian
rupiah both failing sharply.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanahaeminda said Tuesday that the
baht was moving in line with market forces and other regional
currencies.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Thailand, the central bank, has maintained that its
intervention into the currency market would be made only to smooth
out volatility.
</P>
<P>
Anusorn, an economist at Citibank Thailand, said the baht was
expected to continue to show weakness over the next three or four
months.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, trends would improve afterwards, with the
baht showing strength in early 2001 as U.S. interest rates were
expected to stabilize and local interest rates were expected to
climb starting in the second quarter next year.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said one major factor affecting the baht's recent drop
is the recalculation of Thailand's foreign debt held by the
private sector to 18 billion dollars from previous 12 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The weakening baht is unlikely to have a significant impact on
Thai firms, given the lessons learned by local firms about the
importance of risk management, they said.
</P>
<P>
But they also cautioned that if the baht drops below 42 to the
dollar, the result will be higher inflation and an adverse impact
on the trade account and foreign debt holdings.
</P>
<P>
A trading range between 38 and 42 baht to the dollars is
suitable for the economy and will balance the needs of exporters
against those carrying foreign debts, according to the analysts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Killed in U.S. National Guard Helicopter Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Two soldiers aboard a U.S. Army
National Guard helicopter were killed as it crashed Monday night
near Gila Bend in Arizona State, the United States, said reports
reaching here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted Captain Eileen Bienz of the Arizona Army
National Guard as saying that the AH-64 Apache helicopter crashed
on the Barry M. Goldwater Range at about 8 p.m. local time Monday
during night exercises.
</P>
<P>
There have been at least 50 other severe crashes of Apaches
reported since the first delivery of the helicopter to the Army in
1985, among which there have been 14 fatalities, including two
deaths in Albania during a NATO training mission.
</P>
<P>
The Apache, which costs 14.5 million U.S. dollars each, is a
twin- engine army attack helicopter developed by McDonnell Douglas
(now part of Boeing).
</P>
<P>
The Apache carries a mix of three weapons systems: aerial
rockets, a cannon that fires high-explosive ammunition, and
Hellfire missiles. It has been claimed to be the best attack
helicopter in the U.S. Army and is deployed both in the United
States and abroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
