<HEADLINE> Laos Formally Seeks Extradition of 28 Raiders from Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Laos has officially requested the
extradition of 28 armed rebels who were involved in last Monday's
raid on a Lao border checkpoint and are now detained in Thailand,
according to the Thai Foreign Ministry Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The request, which made in a letter sent from the Lao
government recently, asked Thailand to consider sending back "
those robbers who staged the terrorist act" at the border
checkpoint, Thai Foreign Ministry spokesman Don Pramudwinai said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the letter did not formally identify the
charges against the 28 persons.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government said these men will be prosecuted for
illegal entry and possession of illegal weapons according to Thai
laws, before any Lao request is considered, he said, adding it has
urged Laos to present evidence to back up its claims that the 28
were robbers.
</P>
<P>
The letter was conveyed through the Thai embassy in Laos and
received by the foreign ministry Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The 28 men were among over 100 Lao rebels who attacked a Lao
checkpoint last Monday, across Thailand's Sirindhorn border
district in Ubon Rachathani province, 629 kilometers northwest of
Bangkok, and clashed with Lao troops, leading to several injuries
and deaths.
</P>
<P>
The 28 men fled into Thailand and were seized by the Thai
authority after Lao troops repressed the raid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
