<HEADLINE> Duncan to Stay in San Antonio Spurs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Tim Duncan declined an offer
from Orlando Magic to stay with the San Antonio Spurs as he
believed his squad can challenge the Los Angles Lakers for next
year's NBA title.
</P>
<P>
Duncan, who spearheaded the Spurs to win the 1998-99 NBA title,
said on Tuesday that "We have a great opportunity with myself, and
David (Robinson) at the core of the whole thing and the fact that
we have won it before."
</P>
<P>
The Magic offered Duncan a six-year contract worth 67.5 million
U.S. dollars, the biggest under the NBA collective agreement.
However, he could sign a seven-year deal worth 86.5 million U.S.
dollars if he re-signs with San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
Under the NBA rule, no free agents are allowed to sign any
contract until August 1, and Duncan said he felt relieved because
"the process is over and people will stop following me."
</P>
<P>
Duncan was the Most Valuable Player for the championship series
in 1998-99.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old Duncan is the key to San Antonio's future.
Without him, the Spurs would be left with a brand-new 175 million
U.S. dollars arena for the 2002-2003 season without one of the
game's superstars. 
</P>
