<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Locust Campaign Succeeds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The severe plague of summer
locusts, which has affected six million hectares of land and
beaches in China, has now been brought under control, officials
with the Ministry of Agriculture announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
However, they warned that it is still too early to be too
optimistic, since combating autumn locusts could be an even
tougher task as many insects could have survived the summer's
eradication program, and foreign locusts may invade at any time,
today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Locusts have swarmed beaches and mostly uncultivated land
across half of China's provinces, municipalities and autonomous
regions, including Hebei, Henan, Shandong, Tianjin and Xinjiang.
</P>
<P>
Officials revealed that the density of locusts reached 5,000
per square meter in some badly hit regions. In Xinjiang, locusts
devoured 666,000 hectares of grassland and 433,000 hectares of
crops by the end of June.
</P>
<P>
Experts attributed this year's severe locust disaster to
chronic droughts, which left beaches almost uncovered and caused
the water level in reservoirs and lakes to drop. Moreover the
immigration of immense numbers of locusts from foreign countries
has exacerbated the insect infestation in the country.
</P>
<P>
The pest control campaign began in early May. Governments at
all levels have allocated more than 60 million yuan (about 7.23
million U.S. dollars) for pest-control chemicals and equipment.
</P>
<P>
In addition, various ecological control technologies have also
been adopted to combat the insects. For instance, in Xinjiang of
northwest China, over 700,000 trained chickens and ducks chow down
on locusts at the foot of Tianshan Mountain.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Culture Websites to Be Better Regulated: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 12 (Xinhua) -- China will continue to encourage
the development of cultural websites while drafting a set of
regulations to address problems raised by a survey .
</P>
<P>
The survey, released by the Ministry of Culture Tuesday, found
that Chinese Internet users go on the Internet to search for
information, send e-mail and read new rather than appreciate works
of art and literature, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
According to Xu Wenbo, an official in charge of the survey,
most cultural websites on civilization, books and art have very
simple structures and are updated infrequently.
</P>
<P>
Only 17 percent of the 768 investigated websites are updated
daily, and nearly half updated once a month, said the survey.
</P>
<P>
More than half of those surveyed said they are willing to pay
114 yuan (about 17 U.S. dollars) to browse cultural websites.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed that poor content of the cultural websites is
another factor alienating them from the surfers.
</P>
<P>
Some websites simply stick governmental documents on line, some
others tend to only provide entertainment information on movie, TV,
music and pop literature for younger Internet users. In some
extreme cases, however, pornographic materials or materials
infringing upon others' copyrights are flooding in some websites
due to slack regulations on the website.
</P>
<P>
"We should take measures to regulate the industry and establish
more well-designed, influential websites to spread genuine Chinese
culture to the world", said Minister of Culture Sun Jiazheng.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
