<HEADLINE> Basketball New Zealand Keen to Host Worlds Qualifying Series </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Basketball New Zealand is to
ask its Australian counterpart to give up its home-court advantage
for the men's and women's Oceania world championship qualifying
tournaments next year, a Wellington-based newspaper reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It is Australia's turn to host the best-of-three-series which
will decide Oceania's representative for the women's world
championships to be held in China in May 2002 and the men's
tournament in the United States in September 2002.
</P>
<P>
The Dominion said General Manager David Crocker of BNZ wants
the qualifying event played in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Crocker was quoted as saying "There's not been any serious
discussion yet, but I have flagged it with Oceania Basketball
Federation and Basketball Australia's high performance manager
Gary Evans. I wouldn't say we're confident ... but we're hopeful."
</P>
<P>
The Australian men's and women's teams are strong Olympic medal
contenders. They are expected to win through to the respective
2002 world championships.
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand men's team has beaten Australia only once in 35
meets. That was in Wellington, capital city of New Zealand, in
1979. 
</P>
</TEXT>
