Crespo is being exchanged with two Lazio players, Mathias
Almeyda and Sergio Conceicao and 35 billion lire (about 16 million
U.S. dollars) in cash over three years, valuing Crespo at 110
billion lire, at current exchange rates over 52 million U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Crespo deal is expected to be the biggest of the transfer
season in Italy, even though AC Milan, smarting from its poor
performance last season, has been dropping broad hints about a
major purchase in the pipeline and Inter is trying to decide what
to do about the injury-hit Brazilian, Ronaldo.
</P>
<P>
With the arrival of Crespo, there is also speculation that
Lazio's expensive Chilean striker, Marcelo Salas, may be headed
for another club, possibly Inter.
</P>
<P>
The deal is a new world record for soccer transfers. The
previous record was the 90 billion lire paid to Lazio by Inter for
Christian Vieri last year.
</P>
<P>
Crespo is expected to get 3.8 million U.S.dollars net under the
5-year contract.
</P>
<P>
Lazio said all the proposed movements are conditional on being
okayed by the players and clubs.
</P>
<P>
Lazio insiders said Conceicao, who shone in Portugal's national
team in the Euro2000 tournament, was put into the deal at the last
minute because Salas refused to go to Parma. "I'm
disappointed about how Lazio has behaved," he told a Roman radio
later. "I sincerely think I deserved more respect for what I have
given to this club."
</P>
<P>
Cragnotti was saying that he would never let the player go
until a few days ago. The first hint of later developments may
have come as Euro2000 closed with France's victory over Italy in
the final.
</P>
<P>
"I felt very bitter because, during the European championship,
everyone telephoned me with their congratulations for how I played,
especially after my three goals against  Germany, but there was
no call from Lazio," Conceicao told the interviewer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
