<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qingdao, Shandong's Leading Foreign Trade Dealer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINGDAO, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Qingdao, a coastal city in east
China's Shandong Province, has become the largest dealer of
foreign trade in the province as it conducts 82.4 percent of the
total trade done in the province.
</P>
<P>
Imports and exports declared at customs in Qingdao amounted to
11.5 billion U.S. dollars during the first half of this year, a 52.
8 percent rise on a yearly basis.
</P>
<P>
Imports rose 75.6 percent to 4.92 billion U.S. dollars, with
exports growing by 39.3 percent to 6.58 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
More than half of the total foreign trade, or nearly 5.72
billion U.S. dollars, were conducted by means of general trade.
</P>
<P>
And the volume of processing trade with imported raw material
reached 5.21 billion U.S. dollars, a 36.7 percent rise on 1999
figure.
</P>
<P>
Exports by overseas-funded enterprises rose 39.5 percent year-
on-year to 2.91 billion U.S. dollars during the first half of this
year, with the volume by state-run enterprises growing by 28.9
percent to 2.91 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Exports of electro-machinery products declared at local customs
went up 41.4 percent to nearly 1.28 billion U.S. dollars, with
combined export volume of textiles and garments rising 37.5
percent to 1.92 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Japan is still the largest trade partner and the bilateral
trade reached 2.17 billion U.S. dollars during the first half of
this year.
</P>
<P>
Qingdao's other four leading trade partners are the ROK, EU,
the U.S. and Africa in the six-month period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
