<HEADLINE> Relief Supplies to Arrive at Kenyan Port </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Some 29,000 tons of wheat, sorghum,
wheat and yellow maize are expected to arrive at the Indian
Oceanic port of Mombasa in southeastern Kenya this week, the Kenya
Ports Authority said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This is part of international relief agencies' supplies to help
alleviate famine in the eastern Africa. More than 25,000 tons of
yellow maize arrived Tuesday in transit to Uganda.
</P>
<P>
According to the Kenya Ports Authority, the vessel "Hope Well",
which is expected at the port this week, will discharge 1,002 tons
of wheat, 2,505 tons of sorghum and 913 tons of yellow maize for
Somalia and 1,780 bags of yellow maize for Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, millers and commodity dealers in Kenya have imported
more than 28,000 tons of wheat.
</P>
<P>
On July 5, the World Food Program launched an urgent appeal for
aid food for Kenya, saying the country needs 88 million U. S.
dollars to feed an estimated 3.3 million hungry people.
</P>
<P>
In mid-June, Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi announced a duty
waiver on maize imports and encouraged local millers to import
more maize to combat the famine in the country.
</P>
<P>
More maize imports are expected following reports that the
Kenyan government's famine relief program stocks dwindled to less
than 60,000 bags of maize (90 kilograms per bag) at the beginning
of June.
</P>
<P>
President Moi warned in June that 23 million Kenyans, about 80
percent of the country's population, will face the threat of
famine if the prolonged drought persists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
