<HEADLINE> U.N. Refugee Agency Urges to End War in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOME, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations High Commissioner
for Refugees (UNHCR) Sadako Ogata Tuesday strongly appealed to
African leaders to ensure that conflicts in the continent come to
an end and people are protected to live a much more stable and
peaceful life.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference in Lome where she is attending
the 36th annual summit of the Organization of African Unity (OAU),
Ogata said Africa has always been a very large area of refugee
operation in her almost ten years as chief of the U.N. refugee
agency.
</P>
<P>
"I'm very worried about the increase of numbers of refugees
fleeing conflicts and serious violation of human rights," she said.
</P>
<P>
Ogata will complete her term of office at the end of this year
after spending 10 years as the head of the U.N. refugee agency.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony of the OAU summit on Monday, the heads
of state and government paid tribute to her outstanding
contribution to the cause of African refugees.
</P>
<P>
"I hope my successor to pay a lot of attention to Africa," she
said.
</P>
<P>
She told Xinhua that her greatest achievement as high
commissioner is that "we were always open to trying out new ways
to solve problems and devising new methods of doing better in
protection of refugees."
</P>
<P>
"We kept on being very responsive and innovative," she added.
</P>
<P>
"But the failure is that I can not solve more problems than I
have had. The problem is really not just protection of refugees,
but has to do with political solution to the military conflict,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
She complained that "I cannot stop war, I cannot stop serious
violation of human rights, and very often I cannot separate armed
elements from refugees and civilians."
</P>
<P>
According to Ogata, the UNHCR is doing its best to help and
protect refugees fleeing conflicts in Burundi, the Democratic
Republic of the Congo, Sierra Leone, Eritrea and Somalia as well
as displaced persons inside war-torn countries.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR has distributed 300 million U.S. dollars in this
financial year for African refugees estimated at about 5 million,
she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
