<HEADLINE> France Proposes EU Convention on Fight Against Money Laundering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 12 (Xinhua) -- France said Wednesday that it will
intensify the fight against organized crimes, especially money
laundering, with coordinated action of European Union (EU)
countries during its EU rotating presidency.
</P>
<P>
French Minister of Justice Elisabeth Guigou told a meeting of
the European Parliament's Commission of Public Freedom in Brussels
that France calls on the 15 EU members to adopt a convention of
judicial inter-aid in the fight against organized crimes.
</P>
<P>
"The objective is that the banking secrets no longer can be
covered in judicial procedures," she said.
</P>
<P>
The EU countries adopted on May 29 a convention of general
judicial inter-aid, but a convention of judicial inter-aid in
fighting organized crimes is not expected to be adopted by the 15
EU members until a couple of years later, said French officials.
</P>
<P>
The problem of money-laundering was highlighted recently with
the publishing of a "black list" involving 35 countries suspected
to be serving as fiscal havens or centers of money-laundering by
the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development.
</P>
<P>
France will also propose at the Group of Eight summit to be
held later this month in Okinawa, Japan, that the world's most
industrialized nations cooperate in the fight against money-
laundering. 
</P>
</TEXT>
