<HEADLINE> Venezuela Second Oil Byproduct Provider to US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Venezuela ranked second as U.S, oil byproducts supplier,
notwithstanding that Venezuelan exports have been affected by
agreements with the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
(OPEC) to reduce oil output.
</P>
<P>
The South American country represents 14 percent of the total
acquired by the North American country, after Canada, which did
not took part in the supply cut.
</P>
<P>
However, Venezuela occupies fourth place, surpassed by Saudi
Arabia, Canada, and Mexico, if only U.S. imports of crude are
considered.
</P>
<P>
Venezuelan exports to the United States dropped by 90,000
barrels a day between January and February of 1999-2000, while
those from Saudi Arabia and Mexico had an important reduction.
</P>
<P>
Mines and Energy Minister Ali Rodriguez said Tuesday that
Venezuela is one of the five OPEC partners with a capability to
increase production.
</P>
<P>
Venezuela maintains an output quota of 2.92 million barrels a
day, while its potential output is 3.5 million barrels a day,
after the last OPEC decision to increase production.  
