<HEADLINE> France Proposes Common European Residency Card for Foreigners EDS-Rpt With Correction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 12 (Xinhua) -- France proposed Wednesday that the
15 European Union (EU) countries adopt a common residency card for
foreigners who legally live in EU countries for relatively long
periods of time.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a meeting of the European Parliament's Commission on
Public Freedom in Brussels, French Interior Minister Jean-Pierre
Chevenement said that a common residency card will be a progress
and "an essential judicial instrument" to integrate and protect
foreign residents in EU countries.
</P>
<P>
France, which issues a 10-year residency card to the foreign
residents employed by French companies or with professional
credits, proposes that EU countries issue a common residency card
of a duration from eight to 12 years.
</P>
<P>
France, which took over the EU rotating presidency this month,
expects EU countries to obtain an agreement in two years instead
of during its presidency which ends on December 31, said
Chevenement.
</P>
<P>
He also said that France hopes that all EU countries will also
adopt a law guaranteeing "the right of soil" which automatically
offers nationality to the children born in their countries as
France and the United States have been doing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
