<HEADLINE> Guatemala Rejects Honduran Maritime Demarcation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The Guatemalan government has
described as "damaging" to the sovereign interests and rights of
the country the unilateral demarcation of maritime limits made by
Honduras.
</P>
<P>
Guatemalan Foreign Minister Gabriel Orellana said Wednesday
that the Honduran demarcation reduces his country's rights to the
exploitation of maritime regions, according to reports reaching
here from Guatemala City.
</P>
<P>
Honduras did not abide by the standards established by the Sea
Rights Convention for the delimitation of its maritime space in
the Caribbean Sea, said Orellana before the Congress Foreign
Affairs Commission.
</P>
<P>
The Honduran Congress approved in March a decree on the
demarcation of the limits with Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
A Guatemalan Foreign Ministry spokesman said that the Honduras
demarcation is similar to the disposition that caused a
territorial controversy between that country and Nicaragua.
Nicaragua says that the ratification of a treaty of maritime
limits between Honduras and Colombia deprives it of 130,000 square
kilometers of its sea platform in the Caribbean. Nicaragua set in
retaliation customs duties of 35 percent to goods imported from
those two countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
