<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0313 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK House of Commons Speaker to Retire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Britain's House of Commons Speaker
Betty Boothroyd is to retire at the end of the summer after eight
years in the role.
</P>
<P>
Miss Boothroyd, who celebrated her 70th birthday last year,
announced her decision in a short but emotional statement to the
House of Commons Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
She also announced that she would step down as MP for West
Bromwich West. She had a 15,423 majority at the last election,
when she was not opposed by the Conservatives or Liberal Democrats.
</P>
<P>
Miss Boothroyd explained to MPs that she was standing down
after the summer recess this year to give her successor a "good
run-in" before the general election.
</P>
<P>
"It has been a great honor to serve the House as speaker for
more than eight years," she told MPs.
</P>
<P>
Miss Boothroyd was elected speaker in 1992 at the age of 62,
after serving for five years as a deputy. She was the first woman
to take the office.
</P>
<P>
Leader of the House Margaret Beckett responded to the
announcement by saying MPs had heard Miss Boothroyd's statement
with "deep regret," but told her the whole House "took pride and
pleasure in your speakership."
</P>
<P>
Ms Beckett explained that Ms Boothroyd would remain as speaker
during the summer recess, fulfilling outstanding engagements, but
would stand down on October 20 just before parliament resumed.
</P>
<P>
The first day of business will then be given over to electing a
successor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
