<HEADLINE> Canadian Alliance Stresses Election Readiness in Caucus Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Canada's biggest opposition party,
the newly formed Canadian Alliance, stressed its election
readiness in the party's first caucus meeting held Wednesday at
Parliament Hill.
</P>
<P>
Stockwell Day, the party's new leader, stood with three other
former candidates for the Alliance leadership, calling for the
party to "focus for the election which is coming soon."
</P>
<P>
Former opposition leader Preston Manning, Ontarion Tory
strategist Tom Long and Alliance MP Keith Martin were all paying
tribute to Day on a grand show of unity at the gathering in a
reception hall.
</P>
<P>
"The greatest gift that you can give to your new leader is to
unite and pull together this summer," said Manning, who was the
former official opposition Reform Party in Parliament and was
credited for the founding of the 200,000-member Canadian Alliance
party.
</P>
<P>
"Let us enter into the election readiness like we've never
entered before, and then let the Liberal era come to an end, and
let the Alliance era begin," he told the party caucus.
</P>
<P>
Long and Martin also pledged their full support for the 49-year-
old former Alberta treasurer, who won the leadership of the
Canadian Alliance Saturday.
</P>
<P>
According to a latest poll by Canada's National Post newspaper,
the Alliance has narrowed its gap with the ruling Liberals from a
previous 40 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
The poll has found 44 percent in support for the Liberal Party
in a new federal election in contrast to 25 percent for the
Alliance under Day. 
</P>
