<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0321 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Speeds Up Opening Phone Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission Wednesday
announced that the European Union countries should open up their
phone markets by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The opening up is expected to be done through unbundling the
local loop, or the local phone networks monopolized by local
telecoms operators.
</P>
<P>
The governments of the European Union member states set in
March this year the end of 2001 as the deadline for dismantling
the local monopolies in order to spur competition, avoid
overlapping of backbone network buildup, lower tariff and speed
data transmission.
</P>
<P>
Erkki Liikanen, European Union information commissioner, said
Wednesday, "Local loop unbundling is the key to the break-through
of high-speed Internet in Europe and requires strong and urgent
measures."
</P>
<P>
"We need to provide a level playing field across Europe," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The European Union decided in March during its Lisbon summit
that the 15-nation bloc should benefit more from the e-commerce so
as to create more jobs and boost economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Britain and Belgium have already said that they would not be
able to make the deadline. Only Germany and four other smaller EU
nations have opened up their local phone markets while France,
Spain, Italy and Sweden have planned to follow suit by the end of
this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
