<HEADLINE> Most Mexicans Trust Fox: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 12 (Xinhua) -- A poll made in Mexico revealed
Wednesday that most of the people think that President-elect
Vicente Fox will be a good leader and will dispel the 30-year
curse of the persistent economic crisis with the change of
administration.
</P>
<P>
Seventy-one percent of the polled showed confidence in the
future administration of Fox, while eight percent said he will not
be a good leader, and 21 percent did not answer, according to the
Reforma newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Fox, the candidate of the Alliance for Change and winner of the
July 2 elections, will take office on December 1 as the first
president who emerged from the opposition that ended 71 years of
the Institutional Revolutionary Party presidential hegemony.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-three percent of the people asked said that there will
not be a change of government crisis as it has occurred in the
five administrations of the last 30 years, 33 percent forecast the
contrary, and 14 percent chose not to answer.
</P>
<P>
The poll showed that 53 percent expect Fox, 58 years old and
former local Coca Cola Co. executive, will clean his language as
he is bent on using all kinds of turns of language, 43 percent
want him to maintain his style, and 4 percent did not answer.
</P>
<P>
Some 90 percent of those interviewed said that incumbent
president Ernesto Zedillo  acted as he should have, and 6
percent opined against. 
</P>
