<HEADLINE> U.S. Congress Threatens to Withhold Aid to Peru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Congress Wednesday
threatened to withhold aid for Peru as it was displeased with
President Alberto Fujimori to enter his third term in office.
</P>
<P>
Republican Senator Paul Coverdell, the sponsor of the penalty,
said that he raised Congress' attention to the case because the
election of Fujimori "really rattles the premise of democracy" in
the Western hemisphere, meaning not in the interest of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Fujimori was re-elected on May 28, but the United States said
there was fraud and unfairness in the election with the withdrawal
of Fujimori's rival from the poll, and asked Fujimori to fix flaws
in the election system.
</P>
<P>
Coverdell's proposal would give President Bill Clinton 90 days
to certify whether Peru has made significant "progress toward
restoring democracy." If not, sanctions would be applied and 10
million dollar aid would be at stake. And the United States would
also be required to oppose aid to Peru in votes of international
financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
The Peruvian Embassy in Washington issued a statement
criticizing the proposal, calling it a "rash" action conducted
unilaterally by the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
