<HEADLINE> IDB Approves 200 Mln Dls for Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American Development
Bank (IDB) approved Wednesday a 200 million U.S. dollar credit for
Mexico that will be directed to the second phase of a labor force
modernization program.
</P>
<P>
The loan will be reimbursed in 20 years with a two-year grace
period and will have a variable rate of interest of 6.77 percent
at the start, said the IDB in a communique.
</P>
<P>
The IDB supplied resources for 250 million dollars in 1996 for
the first phase of the program, which will cost 850 million
dollars and will be in charge of the Mexican Labor and Social
Prevision Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The Mexican government contributed 166.7 million dollars for
the first phase and will allocate 233.3 million dollars for the
second.
</P>
<P>
The labor force modernization program is aimed at improving the
training of the workers, the reduction of unemployment, and the
promotion of growth in the private sector.  
