<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Should Lift Sanctions: Austria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Austria Wednesday stressed that
it would not block the function of the European Union but its EU
partners should lift the sanctions against it.
</P>
<P>
Austrian Federal Chancellor Wolfgang Schussel told a joint
press conference together with European Commission President
Romano Prodi that his country wanted to have dialogue with its EU
partners and the institutions of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
"We stressed the fact that we want to have dialogue with our 14
partners and the institutions of the European Union because you
cannot make distinctions between bilateral relations and
multilateral relations," said the chancellor.
</P>
<P>
"We will never give up on our rights and are not going to
deliberately block or slow down the important process of the union.
We are very interested in ensuring that the enlargement process
goes ahead properly," he added.
</P>
<P>
The 14 other European Union member states imposed political
sanctions against Austria after the country incorporated the far-
right Freedom Party into the governing coalition on February 4.
</P>
<P>
Austria asked the European Union and its EU partners to
consider lifting the sanctions at the EU summit held at Feira of
Portugal last month but was refused consideration.
</P>
<P>
Portugal, then holding the presidency of the 15-nation bloc,
worked out a plan to deal with the uncomfortable situation between
Austria and its EU partners. A panel of three wise men was
appointed by the European Court on Human Rights to monitor the
human rights status quo in Austria and then to report to the EU
nation holding the rotating presidency, that is now France.
</P>
<P>
The other EU member states will then decide whether to lift the
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Austria, however, wants the sanctions lifted by October 13 and
14 when EU leaders meet for a summit in the French tourism resort
of Biarritz.
</P>
<P>
Schussel welcomed the appointment as the wise men -- former
Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari, former Spanish Foreign
Minister Marcelino Oreja and German law professor Jochen Frowein
who was former vice-president of the European Commission of Human
Rights.
</P>
<P>
The Austrian chancellor said that he was confident that the
three-man panel would give his nation a clean sheet of record on
human rights.
</P>
<P>
France, which took over from Portugal the six-month rotating EU
presidency on July 1, said that it would consider dropping the
political sanctions against Austria if the wise men find Austria
does not violate civil rights and abide by common European values.
</P>
<P>
The French have been one of the hard-line opponents in Austria'
s incorporation of extreme rightists into the country's government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000712.0331 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
