<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Internet Helps Americans Plan Wedding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Nearly half of the engaged-to-
be-married couples in the United States with Web access are using
the Internet to help plan their wedding, according to a study
released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The study, conducted by U.S. marketing information company NPD
Group, found that 48 percent of engaged American couples gathered
information using the Internet and used it to help their wedding.
</P>
<P>
Of these soon-to-be-married couples using the Internet for
wedding planning purposes, 34 percent are engaged females, while
the remaining 14 percent are engaged males. However, the gender
split for the 52 percent who are not using the Internet for
wedding research is more evenly distributed with 28 percent of the
engaged females and 24 percent of the engaged males indicating
that they have not yet logged on to get wedding information.
</P>
<P>
NPD's study is based on data from more than 66,000 surveys
completed in April 2000.
</P>
<P>
"The report confirms the Internet's increasing role in helping
engaged couples plan their wedding," NPD said. "With today's busy
lifestyles, the Web has become a convenient way to get the
information they need to make their wedding a success."
</P>
<P>
Popular Web sites on wedding planning offer information from
wedding gowns, rings, gifts and photos to marriage license,
budgeting, honeymoons and event scheduling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
