<HEADLINE> U.S. Ready to Discuss Peace Process with New Syrian Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Washington said Wednesday that
it was ready to discuss a possible resumption of peace talks
between Israel and Syria after Bashar Assad is inaugurated as
president this week.
</P>
<P>
"We look forward to discussing the status of the peace process
once he has been inaugurated as president," U.S. State Department
spokesman Richard Boucher told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's meeting
with Bashar at his father Hafez Assad's funeral in Damascus last
month, Boucher said "she was impressed with his commitment to the
peace process and she observed that he seems poised and ready to
assume his duties."
</P>
<P>
The 34-year-old Bashar won an overwhelming 97.29 percent of the
vote in a presidential election held Monday.
</P>
<P>
Hafez Assad died of a heart attack on June 10 after he ruled
Syria for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Syrian peace process broke down in January over
differences on the return of the Golan Heights seized by Israel in
the war in 1967. 
</P>
</TEXT>
