<HEADLINE> Mexican President-Elect Presents Security Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Mexican President-elect
Vicente Fox delivered Wednesday a project for the creation of a
security ministry to the country's president of the supreme court
Genaro Gongora.
</P>
<P>
Fox, who will assume office on December 1, told the press that
he is seeking the contribution and opinion of Gongora to the
project.
</P>
<P>
The project foresees reforms on security in the field of the
executive power, the creation of the security ministry, and the
substitution of the Federal Attorney of the Republic Office by the
Prosecutorship of the Nation, said Fox.
</P>
<P>
Fox, winner of the July 2 elections, will become the first
president emerged from the opposition that put an end to 71 years
of the Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI) presidential
hegemony.
</P>
<P>
Fox said that his project aims at closer ties between the
procurement of justice and the enforcement of justice.
</P>
<P>
Fox seeks to strengthen the war against insecurity and
corruption in the country through reforms in the Mexican
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
